<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Pro Sieben TV Network Takes Lead in Going Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Pro Sieben AG today became the first
German television broadcaster to list its shares on the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the Pro Sieben preference shares met strong
interest from about one million private investors who drove the
share price to 95 German marks (54.3 U.S. dollars) on the first
trading day from the originally planned 72 marks (41.1 dollars).
</P>
<P>
"It's a perfect start," the German private TV network said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 850 million shares were ordered, though only 17.5
million will be sold on the market, the company said. The issue
will raise 1.26 billion marks (720 million dollars) for the
company and increase its capital by 360 million marks (206 million
dollars) to more than 700 million (400 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to improve its program, and probably,
to take over other TV broadcasters, the company said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
