<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BA Faces Strike Chaos as Talks Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Air travelers face 72 hours of
chaos when British Airways (BA) cabin crew go on strike after
talks to settle their dispute collapsed last night.
</P>
<P>
BA will be forced to ground thousands of flights from 6am on
Wednesday as each side blamed the other for the latest breakdown.
</P>
<P>
The dispute involve BA's 9,000 cabin crew staff who voted by a
2-1 majority in a secret ballot last month for industrial action.
BA's proposals were accepted by the small breakaway Cabin Crew 89
union.
</P>
<P>
Bill Morris, general secretary of the Transport and General
Workers' Union, said BA wanted a strike and "was prepared to
incite it" no matter what damage was done to the traveling public.
</P>
<P>
However, Robert Ayling, BA chief executive, regretted that the
union was not prepared to resolve the dispute through "reasonable"
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
BA said it now had "no option" but to implement its contingency
plans from Wednesday. These will involve using replacement staff
to do cabin crew work on some flights.
</P>
<P>
It is reported BA is to take out advertisements in newspapers
showing which flights will be operating. The information will also
be on Teletext.
</P>
<P>
BA says it will try to employ "short-term staff and volunteers"
to keep to its schedules.
</P>
<P>
Staff in the company claim that the airline is concentrating on
recruiting a strike-breaking army rather than resolving their
dispute over restructuring contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
