<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Urges "Return of Law" in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- France today urged a "return of the
law" in Cambodia and said it would ask the European Union and the
United Nations Security Council to discuss the emergency situation
in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"France appeals for the rapid return of the law in Cambodia. It
would do its utmost to convince different parties the pressing
necessity for a respect of the constitutional principles adopted
by Cambodia, which is the basis of the democratization process
launched since 1993," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman
Anita Limido.
</P>
<P>
A French government envoy will meet with Cambodia's First Prime
Minister Norodom Ranariddh, who is prolonging his private stay in
France after the coup d'etat in Phnom Penh by Hun Sen, the
country's second prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said that France has made
clear its position to both sides of the Cambodian conflict.
</P>
<P>
"France pleads in this sense, both at the level of its European
partners and the members of the (U.N.) Security Council, in the
framework of the consultations engaged by U.N. Secretary-General
(Kofi Annan)," she said.
</P>
<P>
France has also called on the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN), which has decided to admit Cambodia as a member,
to react to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry Secretary General Bertrand Dufourcq met
today with the ambassadors of six ASEAN nations on the situation
in Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
