<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joulwan: Nato Policy Unchanged About Indictees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Nato's outgoing military chief
General George Joulwan said on Monday that there is no change in
the policy of Nato-led Stablization Force (SFOR) regarding war
crime indictees.
</P>
<P>
"The instructions that I received (on this issue) have not
changed," said Joulwan, who will retire after four years as
Supreme Allied Commander for Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Nato policy has been that SFOR soldiers will not arrest war
crime indictees unless they come across those persons. But some
American media have reported that the Clinton administration is
planning to nab those indicted persons with special forces.
</P>
<P>
Joulwan said that whether there will be a change of the Nato
mandate will be determined by the capitals of the Nato countries.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of war criminals needs to be addressed at the
political level," he said, "what needs to happen is that the
political will needs to be there if I am to receive a different
mandate."
</P>
<P>
Joulwan, who has commanded Nato-led peace-keeping forces for the
past 18 months, said he believed that Western countries should
continue to presure the Bosnian parties to hand in by themselves
the war crime indictees.
</P>
<P>
"I truly believe that the parties themselves must come to grips
with understanding that these indicted war criminals needs to be
brought to justice in the Hague, the parties themselves have this
responsibility," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
