<HEADLINE> France Worried about Tension on Israeli-Lebanese Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- France today expressed worry over the
rising tension on the Israeli-Lebanese border, where Israeli
troops and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah Shiite guerrillas shelled
each other over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried about the renewal of tension on the
Israeli-Lebanese frontier. The grave incidents which expectedly
arrived it seemed from the two sides of the border, the fact that
civilians were attacked, appeared particularly worrying for us,"
said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anita Limido.
</P>
<P>
She said that France lays full confidence in the five-nation
truce monitoring committee for south Lebanon to "circumscribe the
confrontations and protect the civilian population."
</P>
<P>
"France appeals to all the parties to exercise restraint,"
said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The truce monitoring committee, represented by France, Israel,
Lebanon, Syria and the United States, met this morning in the
south Lebanese border town of Naquoura to look into the complaints
about violation of ceasefire filed by both Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Five Lebanese civilians were wounded Sunday night by Israeli
artillery shellings upon some villages in south Lebanon, after
Hezbollah guerrillas launched a rocket attack upon northern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to the ceasefire agreement signed by belligerent
sides on April 26, 1996, both Israelis and Lebanese should spare
civilians from violence and should not launch attacks upon
populated areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
