<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Calls on Justice Ministry Be More Active </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin on Monday called on the Justice Ministry to be more
active in Russian social life.
</P>
<P>
Presenting Sergei Stepashin, the new head of the Justice
Ministry, Chernomyrdin noted that "the Ministry of Justice should
increase its role," while "most control over the government's
lawmaking work" should be concentrated in the Justice Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hatred to the situation that "the country
would live by temporary resolutions and decrees".
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin stressed the need to broaden the functions of the
ministry following Russia's accession to the Council of Europe and
its obligation to bring its legislation in line with European
norms.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also suggested the government should provide
financial support and even a new building for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin is to replace Valentin Kovalyov who has been
dismissed from the ministerial post after a Moscow newspaper
published what it said were stills of a video tape showing him in
a gangland sauna frolicking with naked women.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin declined to comment on the scandal around
Kovalyov, saying that it is "a shame for both the government and
the ministry."
</P>
<P>
However, he criticized Kovalyov for bad work and recalled a
couple of incidents when the minister opposed some document
discussed at a government meeting although earlier it had been
approved by the Justice Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin recently told the Itar-Tass in an interview that he
will start in his new job by restructuring the ministry and
launching a large-scale justice reform.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin headed the Federal Security Service in 1994 and 1995,
but had to step down after Chechen guerrilla's raid on the
southern Russian town of Budennovsk in mid-1995 which claimed over
100 lives.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed head of the administrative department of the
Russian government in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin was appointed justice minister by Russian President
Boris Yeltsin on July 2.  
</P>
</TEXT>
