<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-07 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Israeli Finance Minister to Be Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu is expected to appoint former Justice Minister Yaacov
Neeman as new finance minister soon, possibly late today, ending
weeks of speculation about the cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
In order to complete the long-delayed cabinet reshuffle
following the resignation of former Finance Minister Dan Meridor
last month, Netanyahu held intensive consultations today on the
line-up of the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio reported that Netanyahu could present the
appointment of Neeman as early as tonight to the Knesset
(Parliament) for approval. The Knesset will debate two
non-confidence motions filed by the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Neeman resigned from the justice portfolio last August after
the state prosecution decided to open a criminal investigation
against him for obstructing justice during the investigation of
the bribery case involving Shas Party leader Aryeh Deri. But he
was acquitted of the charges on May 16 by the High Court, which
paved the way for his return to the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
By way of Neeman's appointment, Netanyahu solved the thorny
problem of appointing National Infrastructure Minister Ariel
Sharon to the finance portfolio in his original plan.
</P>
<P>
Sharon has conditioned his transfer to the new post on his
inclusion into the inner security cabinet comprising of Netanyahu,
Foreign Minister David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who has been threatening to leave the coalition in the
past weeks, is reportedly opposed to the inclusion of the
ultra-rightist Sharon into the inner cabinet. He insists on his
sole authority as the man in charge of the peace talks with the
Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has held three meetings with Levy in a bid to solve
the crisis that could topple the government. A deal is said to be
near to define Levy's role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sharon reportedly has given his blessing to Neeman's
appointment following the promise by Netanyahu to grant him a
greater say in the government decision making over security and
diplomatic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak said the prime minister would
consult from time to time with Levy, Mordechai and Sharon on the
security and diplomatic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The reappointment of Neeman, an observant Jew who does not
belong to any party but is closely linked to the religious
communities, was especially welcomed by the religious parties
which are Likud's major ruling partners.
</P>
<P>
The reaction from the opposition camp was mixed. Former
Finance Minister Avraham Shohat of the Labor Party praised
Neeman, who has served as former director-general and attorney of
the Finance Ministry, as a professional candidate.
</P>
<P>
But Shohat also expressed disappointment at Neeman for his
close association with the Orthodox religious parties which are
stalling the peace process with their tough positions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it remained still unclear who would be appointed to
the science portfolio, which has been vacated since former
minister Benny Begin resigned in January to protest the signing
of the Israeli-Palestinian Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Michael Eitan, head of Likud faction in the Knesset, and Likud
lawmaker Silvan Shalom are the two leading candidates for the
science minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Stir Growth by Setting up Small </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) today urged African governments to help
establish small to medium enterprises (SMEs) through research to
stir economic growth and stability.
</P>
<P>
In a report on micro and small enterprises in Africa released
here today, the ILO said governments are increasingly recognizing
the important contributions of SMEs to economic growth and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are, however, not formulating the necessary
policies and providing programs to see to their success, said the
ILO.
</P>
<P>
The report said one of the major impediments to SME
development is that foreign donor agencies, generally influenced
by research from the North, direct research on the crucial
sector.
</P>
<P>
The report said, "their research agenda and implied models of
development often have conformed to their own interests and
perspectives, and had been less attentive to the needs, interests
and development goals of the local users of research findings and
the ultimate beneficiaries."
</P>
<P>
Few entrepreneurs were consulted about research objectives and
the research outcome was ineffective in addressing the pressing
needs, the report said, adding that this wasted limited resources
and undermined local action-oriented research capacity.
</P>
<P>
It suggested demand and action-oriented research which
supports a wide range of SME development be carried out by
professional researchers and non-research stakeholders with
intended beneficiaries also fully involved.
</P>
<P>
SMEs, better known as the informal sector, have been viewed by
most African governments as a method of combating unemployment,
reducing wide income disparities, enhancing national productive
capacities and improving access to basic goods and services in
respect of the poorer majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
