<HEADLINE> 41 Zimbabwean Companies Liquidated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 41 Zimbabwean companies,
mostly in the textile sector, have been liquidated so far this
year compared with 63 for the whole of last year, a business
information and service provider said today.
</P>
<P>
Dun and Bradstreet Zimbabwe Managing Director Fernando Aleixo
said that 16 companies had been declared insolvent so far this
year, up from 18 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
He, however, could not say how many people had lost jobs as a
result.
</P>
<P>
"The section which has been most affected is the textile
industry. This is due to the competition from South Africa and
other countries, and the large amount of second-hand clothing
coming into the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
The other areas also affected included the leather and
engineering sectors which were also facing stiff competition as a
result of the opening up of the economy under the structural
adjustment program, he added.
</P>
<P>
Notable among the companies liquidated last year were Cone
Textiles, one of the country's largest textile concerns which
went into liquidation in 1995 making about 4,000 workers jobless,
the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
