<HEADLINE> FM: Egypt Resists Assassination Attempts on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt is resisting the attempts to
assassinate the Mideast peace process and exerting its utmost to
salvage the peace march, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said today.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the foundered peace process, Moussa said these
endeavors can be realized by not respecting the signed agreements
and planting obstacles before reaching just and balanced peace
whether on Palestinian, Syrian or Lebanese tracks.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and any sensible country in the region should take up
the responsibility for resisting peace-assassination attempts,
Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone concerned with this issue should rescue the peace
march from such attempts," he added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Palestinian leader's call for holding an Arab
Summit to confront Israeli recalcitrance, Moussa said that the
Arabs maintain consultations to handle the situation. However, no
date or venue has been determined as yet, according to Moussa.
</P>
<P>
The top Egyptian diplomat dismissed the question that major
world powers are not concerned with Israeli attempts to blow up
peace, saying that everyone is trying to salvage the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"We can not accuse anyone of condoning the serious crisis
facing the peace drive," Moussa said. "Neither the U.S., Russia,
nor Europe could accept that," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We all shoulder the responsibility of salvaging the peace
process and restoring the basic principle of the peace march,
namely land for peace," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The summit of the seven industrialized states plus Russia
recently held in Denver, U.S., stressed that the peace process
can not be salvaged except through the land for peace principle,
he added.
</P>
<P>
International mediating efforts have failed to bring the
Palestinians and Israelis back to the negotiating table three
months after the peace talks collapsed when Israel began building
a new neighborhood for Jews.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has stepped in as the main mediator between the two
sides over the past few weeks as a result of what many Arabs
perceive as a lack of U.S. interest in the peace process.
</P>
