</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair backed Mowlam in the Northern
Ireland peace efforts and pledged to press on with the search for
peace through year-old Northern Ireland talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to go on searching for peace. We will not give
up, even for a moment," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, called for
"calm and dignified" protests, saying the rioting was
counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein president Gerry Adams said: "We want to call for an
end to the hijackings and burnings."
</P>
<P>
The display of firepower by the Irish Republican Army in
overnight unrest across the divided province was the biggest in
years and the outpouring of nationalist fury appeared to mark the
end of any honeymoon with Britain's new Labor government. 
</P>
