<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-07 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Bank Chief Calls for Combating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Central Bank chief today
urged regulatory authorities worldwide to adopt appropriate
measures to combat money laundering, stressing that fighting money
laundering is an international problem.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Central Bank of Cyprus Afxentis Afxentiou was
speaking at a three-day international conference on money
laundering which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
He called upon regulatory authorities worldwide to remain
vigilant, keeping under constant review the development of new
money laundering techniques.
</P>
<P>
The conference will examine issues such as the impact of
organized crime on national and the world financial systems, and
suggestions for developing a response to international organized
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Afxentiou revealed that the amount of money laundered each year
in the world's financial system exceeds 500 billion U.S. dollars,
noting that the vastness of the amounts of money involved poses a
severe danger to the world financial system, threatening the
smooth functioning of financial markets.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that 70 percent of laundered funds are drug-
related, while other offenses include illegal arms deals,
premeditated murders, abduction, smuggling and product
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
It seems that organized crime is turning into "a threat to most
of us, to financial institutions, and to the society as a whole,"
Afxentiou said.
</P>
<P>
The abolition of exchange controls in most countries and
liberalization and globalization of financial markets have
facilitated money laundering, the governor added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that organized crime can now operate across
national borders more easily and speedily, taking advantage of
the latest technological innovations, such as electronic banking
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, participants from the United States,
Britain, Switzerland and other countries will express their
views and submit suggestions on efforts to combat money
laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
