<HEADLINE> Military Junta Faces Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 7 (Xinhua)- Six weeks after seizing power from
the civilian government of president Tejan Kabbah, the military
junta in Sierra Leone is now faced with a shortage of petroleum
products including black oil to generate electricity in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, motorists have been queuing to buy only
three gallons of petrol for each vehicle. Most queues run as far
as a mile and obervers say if the trend continues, a long stretch
is likely to build up as from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the state-run National Petroleum
(NP), the ration "will shortly be reduced to two gallons".
</P>
<P>
"We are nearly reaching the bottom of the barrel. We usually
have a three month buffer stock but this is what we have been
using since the coup. No order has yet been placed and oil
tankers have been frightened off by the insecurity of the
situation".
</P>
<P>
A west African diplomat noted that the main bulk of petroleum
imports come from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Given the present chill between Abuja and the Junta in
Freetown, I doubt whether the Nigerians would be prepared to send
a single drop", he told Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Under Sierra Leone's structural adjustmant programme, the
World Bank for the past three years has been paying for all oil
importation into the country. The commodity is then sold and the
money recycled for fresh imports.
</P>
<P>
The bank has however suspended all assistance on June 19 as a
reaction to the May 25 coup and canncelled nine other projects
according to Mamadou Diallo, country officer for Sierra Leone at
the bank's Washington office in a letter sent to finance ministry
officials here.
</P>
<P>
They include agricultural sector support of 21,000,000
dollars, infrastructural project for Freetown, 26,000,000
dollars, techmical assistance, 10,000,000 dollars, urban water
supply 36,000.000 dollars, transport sector 35,000,000 dollars
and housing sector, 20,000,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Diallo, total figues in terms of commitments is
about 264.65 million dollars which has now been cancelled.
</P>
<P>
"Any decision to resume any World Bank programme will depend
on the extent to which present conditions chance", he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
