<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Gravity Flow Scheme Improves Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- For the past ten years, Uganda has
carried out a Gravity Flow Scheme (GFS) in a bid to improve
people's sanitation status, enabling about 300,000 people
currently to benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
GFS refers to a water supply system whereby water is tapped
from a spring, river or lake and transported through pipes to
communal taps in lower areas. There is no need for external power
to transport the water because the water source is at a higher
altitude than all the other points of the system.
</P>
<P>
Therefore it is a method for people to spend little money to
access safe drinking. "Users of the scheme normally pay only
between 400 shillings and 500 shillings (1,050 Ugandan shillings
equal to one U.S. dollar) per cubic metre of the water," said Mr.
Kisembo who is in charge of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
In the last ten years, cooperative arrangements have been
established between non-governmental organisations, donors,
public bodies and local communities to carry out the scheme while
central government has been responsible for resource mobilisation
and technical support to districts in the country through
district water offices.
</P>
<P>
Up to now 45 GFS are operational and, as a result, 300,000
Ugandans are getting access to safe drinking water and improved
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 34 schemes are under construction, 24 schemes have
been designed and 77 schemes have been identified with potential
for development.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugandan Ministry of Natural Resources, when fully
developed by the year 2000, these 135 schemes can benefit a total
of 800,000 people.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by the ministry shows that at least another
150 potential sources exist to meet the needs for a further
700,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Therefore it is evident that sufficient gravity flow schemes
potential exists to benefit approximately 1.5 million people in
the country, which is about 9 percent of the total population.
</P>
<P>
In other words, the GFS potential may contribute significantly
to increase the safe water coverage to 35 percent of the rural
areas at present. The figure has been steadily increasing at an
average rate of 1-2 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is endowed with rich water resources, for 15 percent of
the country is covered by lakes and rivers. Ground water reserves
are also adequate in most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite these favorable conditions, however, 65 percent of the
population cannot get access to safe drinking water at present.
This causes constant incidences of water related diseases such as
cholera, dysentery and Guinea worm in the country, resulting in
high mortality rate especially among children.
</P>
<P>
For the rest 35 percent of the population who can drink safe
water, 2.85 million get it by boreholes and 262,800 people get it
by shallow wells, whereas 3.091 million obtain it by protected
springs and 50,000 by rain water catchment, besides 300,000 by
GFS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
