<HEADLINE> Value of Building Permits Up in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The value of building permits issued for
housing in Canada rose for the second consecutive month in May,
although non-residential construction levels were off, Statistics
Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
Municipalities issued permits for housing worth 1.1 billion U.S.
dollars, up 1.4 percent from April. This followed declines in both
long- and short-term mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the value of non-residential permits dropped after four
consecutive increases. Permits were down 28.6 percent in May to 630
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The level in April was exceptional, the highest in almost seven
years," the agency noted.
</P>
<P>
Overall, municipalities issued 1.7 billion in building permits in
May, down 12 percent in the wake of non-residential decline.
</P>
<P>
Permits for single-family dwellings dropped one percent, but
multiple-family units were up 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the non-residential sector, commercial permits fell 29 percent,
industrial building plans were off 30.8 percent and institutional
construction was down 24.7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
