<HEADLINE> 7 Killed Amid Riot Before Kenya's Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes between the police
and opposition supporters broke out in Nairobi and some other
major Kenyan towns today, claiming at least seven lives and
causing leading business there to an almost complete standstill.
</P>
<P>
Local reports quoted police sources as saying that two men
were killed in Nairobi during the day-long disturbance with four
people in the Nyahururu town and one in Thika. Both towns are
located near the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Among the four victims in Nyahururu, two were crushed to death
when a crowd stampeded as the police moved in, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kamotho, chief of the ruling Kenya African National
Union (KANU), later strongly condemned the violence caused as
soon as the illegal rallies seeking for constitutional reforms
were broken up by the police in these towns.
</P>
<P>
Violence can only "derail the country from the process of
democracy" and "make the impending general elections impossible,"
he warned in a statement issued this evening.
</P>
<P>
The KANU has already put general elections at the first place,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that this year's fiercest game of "cat and
mouse" was seen today between more than 4,000 policemen and
thousands of demonstrators around main streets of Nairobi, where
most shops had been closed and many barricaded against looters.
</P>
<P>
Along Jogoo Road, nearby the planned rally venue of Kamakunji
Ground, conflicts had lasted for hours between the stone-armed
crowd and the police firing tear-gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
Huge stones were scattered along the road, several cars were
smashed and heavily pounded there. Ambulances marked with red
cross and trucks of police with shields were back and forth while
military carrier planes whistling overhead.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of protesters were said to be severely beaten by the
police during the so-called Saba Saba rally. Saba Saba means the
date of July 7 in Kiswahili. On the day seven years ago, at least
20 people were killed during a similar Nairobi rally.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the opposition leaders announced they would hold the
Saba Saba rallies in some 50 towns in the eastern African
country, disregarding the banning order from the government and
its warning of breaking-up.
</P>
<P>
An estimate of far more than 10,000 police had been deployed
around the scheduled rally site across the country days before
when the government rejected to issue a license to the rallies.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders said the rallies were designed to press for
constitutional reforms and direct dialogue between the government
and the opposition before the general elections whose date is yet
to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
However, the KANU lashed out at the rally plan, charging it
was "a plan by the opposition to disrupt normal business and
endanger lives of innocent citizens."
</P>
<P>
The opposition disrupted reading of the budget in parliament
on June 19 and failed to hold two rallies due to police
intervention by force in Nairobi in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
