<HEADLINE> S. Leone to Hold 1st Court Martial Since Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The first court-martial in Sierra
Leone since the May 25 coup is to be held within 24 hours,
military spokesman Major John Milton said today.
</P>
<P>
"A dismissed soldier who was serving a jail sentence for
robbery will be the first accused to appear before the
(court-martial) session," he said, quoted by a report reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
According to prison officials, the soldier, whose name has not
been released, was among hundreds of inmates, including military
leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who sprung from jail in the wake
of the coup that toppled the country's elected government.
</P>
<P>
The ex-soldier was accused of killing a young woman in the
east of the capital Freetown on Sunday, the report said. 
