<HEADLINE> Russia Hails Tajik Reconciliation Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Monday welcomed the starting of the Tajik national
reconciliation commission, describing it as a "qualitatively new
stage and the first practical step towards the implementation of
the inter-Tajik agreements".
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the commission was held today in Moscow's
President Hotel to settle the conflicts in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Primakov at the opening meeting stressed the fundamental
importance of the efforts to be taken by the Tajik government and
the opposition in order to make sure that the implementation of
the inter-Tajik agreements "moves forward on a planned basis in
strict compliance with the established deadlines."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need to "fully use the accumulated positive
experience of talks and promote mutual understanding and trust in
the name of the highest interests of the Tajik people," adding
that Russia will "closely watch" the commission's work and "do
everything possible to make its work fruitful."
</P>
<P>
Commission Chairman Said Abdullo Nuri, one of the opposition
leaders, and his deputy Abdulmadzhid Dostiyev, who is Tajik
parliament first deputy chairman, thanked the U.N., the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe and observer
countries, particularly Russia, for their contribution to
achieving national reconciliation at the various stages of
inter-Tajik talks.
</P>
<P>
Nuri expressed his hope that the commission will adopt
decisions "reflecting the interests of both sides, dispelling
doubts and opening up the way to peace and national accord."
</P>
<P>
Dostiyev noted that the people selected to serve on the
commission "do not express the interests of some parties, groups
or regions," adding that they value "the interests of the nation
and Tajik statehood more than anything else."
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was attended by 26 members of the commission
(13 from each side), experts, U.N. special envoy to Tajikistan
Gerd Dietrich Merrem and the ambassadors of the countries
participating in the Tajik peace process.
</P>
<P>
The commission was set up in accordance with the decision
adopted at the talks between Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov and
Nuri in Moscow last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
