<HEADLINE> Big Grant to Be Issued for Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the Global
Environmental Facility (GEF) will soon release 70 million U.S.
Dollars for curbing water hyacinth, pollution and improving
fisheries in Lake Victoria, Africa's largest freshwater lake.
</P>
<P>
The money will be managed by the Lake Victoria Environmental
Management Program (LVEMP), co-established last year by the three
eastern African countries around the lake -- Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda, LVEMP chief C. Nyirabu said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the money, Kenya will get 24.5 million Dollars with
Tanzania 20.4 million Dollars and Uganda 25 million Dollars, he
was quoted by the Kenyan News Agency as saying in Kisumu, the
third-biggest Kenyan city ashore the 68,800-square-kilometer
lake.
</P>
<P>
Water hyacinth, one of the fastest-growing plants in the world
which is posing a mounting threat to choke the second-largest
freshwater lake on the earth, should be removed through
biological, manual and mechanical means, he noted, excluding
chemical means.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, reports said Uganda, the most-affected country by
water hyacinth in the region, is likely to apply chemicals
against the weed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
