<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Italy's Economic Convergence Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers of the 15 EU
member states today approved the economic convergence plan
submitted by the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the European Council of Finance Ministers held
here Monday, the EU finance ministers expressed their satisfaction
with the plan, which covers the period from 1998 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government, which is aiming to reduce its deficit
to join the first wave of European Monetary Union (EMU) due in
1999, vowed that it would take concrete measures to ensure its
financial stability.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the EU finance ministers asked Italy to spare
no effort in its structural reform, especially in the social
sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the convergence plan, Italy is planning to reduce its
budget deficit to 2.8 percent of its gross domestic product (GDP)
in 1998, 2.4 percent in 1999 and 1.8 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the percentage of Italy's national debts to its
GDP is planned to be lowered to 121.1 in 1998 and 116.3 percent in
2000. The economic growth rate will be increased from 1.2 percent
in 1997 to two percent in 1998, 2.5 percent in 1999 and 2.7
percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The plan also forecasts the inflation rate of Italy in 2000 to
be 1.5 percent, 0.3 percent down from that in 1998. The jobless
rate will fall to 10.4 percent in 2000 from 11.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
