<HEADLINE> ECA, UNDP to Hold Forum on Governance in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) and the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) will jointly hold a high-level forum this week on
the state of governance in Africa.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the ECA today, which added that the
forum will provide a platform for Africans, international
organizations and Africa's external partners in the donor
community to engage in a dialogue on the state of governance in
the region through the medium of national governance programs.
</P>
<P>
Governance is an integral theme of the United Nations
System-wide Special Initiative for Africa (UNSIA) unveiled in
March 1995.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the ECA said, at least 16 African
countries are expected to participate in the forum, which will
give the participating African countries an opportunity to
articulate their positions on a number of issues, including
constitutional and judicial reform, electoral and parliamentary
assistance, empowerment with reference to civil society, civic
education, non-governmental organizations, private sector and
communications and media.
</P>
<P>
African development, political and social-economic issues,
critical issues relating to governance in Africa, responses and
programs initiated by African and international partners and the
African perspective on governance will all be under the
spotlight, the release added.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the forum also include the Organization of
African Unity, the African Development Bank (ADB), Global
Coalition for Africa (GCA), nine United Nations system agencies
and other international organizations as well as 18 donor
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
