<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-07 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Vows to Enhance Secularism and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz today reiterated that his government will spare no effort
to safeguard Turkey's secularism and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Announcing his government's program in the parliament, Yilmaz
said that the newly established tripartite coalition government
will save the country from the political crisis caused by the
former Welfare Party-led administration.
</P>
<P>
He promised that his government will do its utmost to
reinstate the reputation of the state establishment and to
strengthen the country's constitutional democracy and secularist
system.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, also chairman of the Motherland Party, emphasized
that the new government will try to establish "a culture of
compromise" in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Showing the government's determination to fight
fundamentalism, the program said that the compulsory primary
education will be extended from the current five years to eight
years.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a basic aim (of the government) to train people
equipped with the knowledge and capability to deal with the
information age and assimilate Ataturk (founder of Turkey)'s
principles and reforms," it said.
</P>
<P>
The program also vowed to firmly fight political corruption in
order to create a clean government.
</P>
<P>
As to the issue of the southeastern region, the program
expressed the determination that the new government will
continue its battle against separatists in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it also promised that the government will help the
underdeveloped region in expanding its economy.
</P>
<P>
On Turkey's foreign policy, the program said that Turkey will
continue to strengthen its ties with the United States, Europe,
Russia as well as Asian countries on the basis of mutual
benefits.
</P>
<P>
It noted that Turkey's full accession to the European Union
is not just a goal, but a right of Turkey which has long been
making efforts to join the European bloc.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the Cyprus issue, the program said that Turkey
will keep on enhancing its traditionally friendly relations with
northern Cyprus and will give support for it in all fields and by
all means.
</P>
<P>
The parliament is reportedly to start a general debate on the
government's program Thursday and a vote of confidence is
scheduled for July 12.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz became the new prime minister after President Suleyman
Demirel approved the new cabinet list submitted by Yilmaz on
June 30.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that the Yilmaz government will have less
difficulty in winning a vote of confidence in the parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
