<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Appeals for Calm, End to Hijackings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republican Army, today urged Roman Catholic youths to be
calm and stop car hijackings and burnings in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams called on nationalists "to be
calm, to be disciplined, to refuse to accept the burden of second
class citizenship."
</P>
<P>
He said even he himself saw the hijacking of a truck in west
Belfast on his way to a meeting today.
</P>
<P>
"We just discovered that some young people had hijacked this
lorry and we are trying to return it to its owner," he told local
reporters.
</P>
<P>
A Catholic national violence erupted overnight in Northern
Ireland after the pro-British Protestants were allowed to march
through a Catholic area of Portadown Sunday, with hundreds of
cars, trucks and buses being hijacked and burned.
</P>
<P>
However, despite his appeals, local Catholics, who are strongly
opposed to the parades of the Protestants, were still burning
vehicles only a short distance from where he was speaking,
according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Across Northern Ireland, Catholic young people used the
well-worn tactic of hijacking cars, setting them on fire and then
stoning or throwing petrol bombs at emergency services and police
and small scale violence was still going on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
