<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR Denies Troops on High Alert in Federation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The NATO-led Stablization Force
(SFOR) today denied a report by the Bosnian Serb media that troops
in the Muslim-Croat federation are on high alert.
</P>
<P>
According to SFOR spokesman Chris Riley, the Bosnian Serb news
agency, SRNA, Sunday carried a letter presumably written by Serb
army Chief of Staff Pero Colic to the Serb republic's President
Bilijana Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
The letter claimed that soldiers had not been released from
service in the military forces of the federation and were
currently in a "heightened state of readiness."
</P>
<P>
"The SFOR constantly monitors the activities of the entity
armies and there are no indicators at present to suggest that the
Federation Army is preparing to take any action against the VRS
(Serb army)," Riley said.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic has been in a political confrontation with her
colleagues in Pale whom she accused of corruption. The letter,
written in the name of Colic, has warned Plavsic of consequences
that the political crisis is bringing on the Serb entity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
