<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Hopes for Peaceful Settlement of Cambodia Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States today called
on both parties concerned in Cambodia's violent conflict to
restrain themselves so that no further violence could be
rekindled.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia has been sliding into chaos over the past two days as
troops backing each of the country's two prime ministers battled
with rockets, artillery and small arms in the streets of the
capital of Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
Reports said forces loyal to Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, who
launched the attack, tried to control the capital while First
Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh was abroad in Paris and
his party had said they would not give up.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters
that the United States was deeply concerned at the violence and
loss of life caused by the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We called on the authorities (of Cambodia) to take decisive
measures, to prevent further violence," Burns said at a regular
briefing. "We urge Cambodia's leaders to resolve their political
difference peacefully, and abide by the principles of the Paris
peace accords."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also called
on the rival factions to settle their differences peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"What we believe is important is that the various contending
parties solve their problems through peaceful means and not
military means," Albright told a news conference in Madrid where
she is to attend a NATO summit Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States was consulting this afternoon with
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries in the
State Department over the situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of that meeting is to exchange information with
them and to share our respective assessments over the meaning, the
political meaning of what happened over the weekend," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would hope that all of us internationally could agree that
we ought to coalesce to argue for an end to the fighting and for
the recommencement of some kind of political cooperation between
the two co-prime ministers and their political parties so that the
people of Cambodia do not have to live through a civil war," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States has not contemplated any kind of
evacuation at the moment of American citizens in Cambodia as the
fighting has subsided over the last 24 hours. But he strongly
recommended that American citizens "defer travel to Cambodia for
the time being." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
