<HEADLINE> Japan Suspends Aid to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan has decided to suspend its
Official Development Assistance (ODA) for fiscal 1997 to Cambodia
until the country's political unrest subsides, Japanese Foreign
Minister Yukihiko Ikeda said here today.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for Japan to confirm that the situation in
Cambodia is stable before extending assistance to it," Ikeda said
after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Foreign Ministry has already halted a dispatch of
experts scheduled to leave for Cambodia on Wednesday to study the
development of industrial complexes there.
</P>
<P>
The complexes is part of Japan's ODA program for fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
Japan has pledged to provide some 8 billion yen (70 million
dollars) in loans to Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
