<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IGAD Summit Urges End on Sudan, Somalia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today called for end to conflicts in Sudan and Somalia while
opening a two-day regional summit attended by leaders from six
eastern and northeastern African countries.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda of the sixth Inter-Governmental Authority
on Development (IGAD) summit is Sudan's crisis and its thorny
ties with Eritrea, Ethiopia and Uganda, especially the fate of
114 Sudanese prisoners of war held by Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The summit is attended by President Moi, his counterparts Omar
el-Bashir of Sudan, Hassan Aptidon of Djibouti and Issaias
Afeworki of Eritrea, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and
Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Foreign
Affairs Eriya Kategaya.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) leader John
Garang arrived here Monday before the summit. He said he has come
only for consultations and would not attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
SPLA has fought in southern Sudan since 1983 for greater
autonomy of the Christian south from the Moslem north and now is
allied with armed opposition groups in northern Sudan with
battles continuing in the north as well as in the south.
</P>
<P>
"We must bring the escalation of the conflict in eastern and
northern Sudan to the forefront and find a quick solution by
urging all parties in the conflict to pursue peace," urged Moi,
who is also the IGAD chairman, in his opening speech.
</P>
<P>
"In order to break the impasse, the talks must be resumed by
all parties in the conflict so that a lasting solution can be
found," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The IGAD held two high-level meetings in 1994 on the crisis in
Sudan but the talks were deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has accused for a long time its
fellow-IGAD members Eritrea, Ethiopia and Uganda of sending
troops over the border to fight alongside rebels.
</P>
<P>
In response, Uganda accuses Sudan of providing havens and
support for a northern Ugandan rebel group, the Lord's Resistance
Army (LRA), which has been fighting for 10 years in a bid to
topple Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni.
</P>
<P>
Moi today also called for peace and stability restored in
Somalia and expressed regret that "leaders in Somalia have not
seen it fit to take seriously the suffering of the people,
particularly women and children."
</P>
<P>
"I hope that Somali leaders will realize that the primary
responsibility for finding a negotiated settlement is in their
own hands and that they must put their heads together to stop the
suffering of their people," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's chair is vacant at the seven-member IGAD summit as
usual because it has not had a central government since 1991 when
clan leaders combined to oust former leader Mohamed Siad Barre
and then brought the Horn of African nation into a war-torn
state.
</P>
<P>
IGAD was set up in 1986 for enhancing cooperation on
anti-drought and economic development among the member countries.
Regional political affairs have been on its agenda since 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"We all have an obligation to support a strong IGAD in order
to move toward the realization of the African Economic
Community," Moi added when presiding over today's summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
