<HEADLINE> 75 Percent of Vehicles in Dhaka Emit Black Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Of some 250,000 motor vehicles plying
in the roads of Bangladesh's capital Dhaka, a staggering 75
percent emitted black smoke into the air, according to an official
at the government's Environment Directorate.
</P>
<P>
What is more, a substantial number among these defaulted
vehicles were owned and managed by the government, the official
said on condition of anonymity, adding that almost half of these
vehicles had the necessary fitness certificates provided by the
authority.
</P>
<P>
These offending motor vehicles emitted threatening quantity of
carbon monoxide, hydrocarbon and lead into the air causing severe
health disorders like lung cancer and asthma.
</P>
<P>
Deeming the level of air pollution in Dhaka as one of the
highest in the world, he said that previously Mexico city had the
reputation of being the worst polluted city on earth.
</P>
<P>
But at present, he informed, the level of toxic lead
contamination in Dhaka's air far surpassed that of its Mexican
counterpart.  
</P>
</TEXT>
