<HEADLINE> Canada Sees Record Mergers This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian companies are on track for
a record year of mergers and acquisitions, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of transactions in Canada increased 21 percent to
628 in the first half of this year from 521 in the same period of
last year, according to a survey by the Toronto-based Crosbie &AMP;
Co. Inc..
</P>
<P>
Canadian businesses are on target to break last year's record
number of deals of 1,185 as well as the 1995 record for the total
annual value of transactions of 56 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
To the end of June, the combined value of all mergers and
acquisitions was 32.7 billion dollars, up from 25.2 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very buoyant environment from the point of view of
doing transactions," Alan Crosbie, managing partner of the
company, was quoted as saying by the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"I just don't see anything that is going to cause this to
change," he said.
</P>
<P>
Low interest rates, a strong economy and a move toward
globalization are the key reasons for the increased activity, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The biggest deals so far this year include the 3.2 billion
dollars merger of Abitibi-Price Inc. and Stone Consolidated Corp.
and the 1.7 billion bid for London Insurance Group Inc. by Royal
Bank of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
