<HEADLINE> Industrial Vacancy Rate Drops in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The vacancy rate of industrial
buildings in Canada fell a full percentage point to 6.3 percent in
the first six months of this year, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The drop is the steepest slide in the past three years,
according to a new survey by the Toronto-based real estate
services company Royal LePage Commercial Inc..
</P>
<P>
"It means there is a real head of steam growing for
construction. There is no such thing as bad real estate anymore,"
said a senior vice-president of the company.
</P>
<P>
"Not only are these numbers promising from a real estate
perspective, they are also a harbinger for job creation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The real estate market is being driven by the low Canadian
dollar, low inflation and improved consumer confidence, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative value of all industrial permits issued in Canada
in the first five months of this year was up 22 percent from a
year earlier, according to Statistics Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
