<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Announces New Budget Request Rules for Fiscal 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government today rolled
out new rules to cut budgetary spending and move toward restoring
the nation's deficit-ridden state finances by the target year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Effective from fiscal year 1998, the guidelines for budgetary
requests will cap government ministries and agencies' expenditure
growth according to the policy sectors they are involved.
</P>
<P>
They will replace the current system under which the cabinet
decides limits on budgetary growth for each ministry and agency, a
Kyodo News report quoted Finance Ministry officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, general account expenditures for fiscal
1998 starting next April 1 will be cut by 240 billion yen (2.1
billion U.S. dollars), or 0.5 percent off the fiscal 1997 level,
to about 43,560 billion yen (385.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
To improve the efficiency of fund allocation, the system sets
aside a special outlay of 550 billion yen (4.9 billion dollars)
for areas deemed important for economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The measures, which were recommended in June by the Conference
on Fiscal Structural Reform, a forum headed by Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto, were approved at a cabinet meeting this morning.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the new system sets quantitative reduction targets
on major spending ranging from public works to official
development assistance (ODA) for foreign recipients.
</P>
<P>
Outlays for Japan's ODA program in fiscal 1998 will be cut by
10 percent or 110 billion yen (970 million dollars) from the
previous year, the Finance Ministry officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brisk Market for Hydroplanes South of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Light-duty hydroplane transport has
a brisk market potential in the southeastern part of China, an
area rich in water resources, according to a civil aviation expert.
</P>
<P>
The area, south of the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
river, has not enough land airports, while it would take up too
much arable land to build a new airport, said Pan Jichun, an
engineer with the Changzhou Aircraft Manufacturer, in east China's
Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
A small airport of 20 ha would cause the loss of more than 80
tons of grain annually, he said, adding that in China each airport
has to serve an area of 90,000 sq km on average, 18 times the
world average.
</P>
<P>
China's major freshwater lakes are all located on the middle
and lower reaches of the Yangtze, including Taihu, Hongze and
Poyang lakes. In addition, the area has a number of large
reservoirs. "The conditions here are very beneficial for
developing hydroplane transport," said Pan.
</P>
<P>
A hydroplane port needs a special water surface of only 1,000 m
long and 65 m wide, according to him.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces can both introduce
60 to 70 hydroplanes to cater to the growing numbers of business
travelers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
While speeding up research and development of China's own
hydroplanes, foreign hydroplanes can be introduced to the Yangtze
area first, Pan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM: Cabinet Shifted to Improve Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's limited cabinet reshuffle
today is aimed at boosting efficiency in the government, said
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
"The present stage requires speed and decisiveness in
performance in various domains of production and services,"
Ganzouri told reporters after the swearing-in of the ten new
ministers.
</P>
<P>
In the shake-up, some ministries were split up to create new
ones like ministries of environment and higher education,
according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"Some changes were made to take the burden off some big
ministries such as education... while environment is coming up as
another important concern," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the new appointees that took the constitutional oath
before President Hosni Mubarak at the presidency headquarters,
four of them are first timers in the cabinet which has remained
intact since Ganzouri took office in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mufeed Shihab, rector of Cairo University, was assigned the
post of minister of higher education and minister of state for
scientific research affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Abdel Halim Abu Zeid, chairman of the Water Resources
Conservation Research Center, will head the Ministry of Public
Works and Water Resources to replace the late minister Abdel-Hadi
Radi who died last November.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassadress to Japan Mervat el-Talawi takes charge of
the Ministry of Insurances and Social Affairs. And Nadia Riyad
Makram, who was in charge of women and development affairs at the
UN Development Program, was chosen for environment minister.
</P>
<P>
The three drop-outs from the 32-member cabinet, all women
including the economy minister, were either criticized for
mismanagement and inefficiency or simply accused of staying in the
cabinet for too long.
</P>
<P>
Three key ministers -- Defense Minister Mohamed Hussein
Tantawi, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Interior Minister Hassan
el-Alfy -- retain their posts.
</P>
<P>
The appointments were made this morning during a session
between Ganzouri and these new appointees.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet reshuffle is to be followed by a governorship
shake-up in a drive to speed up the country's economic
development, according to local press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
