<HEADLINE> Uganda Peace-Keepers to be Deployed on OAU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's peace-keeping detachment,
to be trained by U.S. Green Beret soldiers, will be deployed once
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) permits, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
Amama Mbabazi, the State Minister for Defense, told ''The
Monitor'' paper here Monday, what attracted the Uganda army in
U.S. Green Beret Unit training is its building capacity.
</P>
<P>
But deployment of the detachment must be consulted with the
OAU, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
''Building capacity is one thing and deploying that force is
another,'' Mbabazi told the newspaper. ''We can train and develop
capacity, when it comes to deploying that force, we have to get
the mandate from the OAU,'' said the official.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time a high-ranking official stated his
point of view on the matter.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report said some 60 U.S. Green Beret soldiers will
arrive within a week to train an 800-men battalion for two
months.
</P>
<P>
The object of the training is to create rapidly deployable
peace-keeping troops of eight to 10 battalions under the auspices
of the United Nations and the OAU. They would be sent to such hot
spots in Africa as Congo (Brazzaville) to help maintain peace
there.
</P>
<P>
U.S. soldiers will train army men from Senegal, Tunisia,
Ethiopia, Ghana, Mali and Malawi later this year under the same
plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
