<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Favors International Mobilization Over Cambodian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it favors an
international mobilization to pressure the conflicting sides of
Cambodia to resume dialogue over the present crisis in their
country.
</P>
<P>
"Faced with the fullness of the crisis, the mobilization of the
international community is necessary," said a spokesman of the
French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
France invites different parties in Cambodia to show moderation
and to resume as soon as possible dialogue aimed at going out of
the present crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
This message was delivered by the Assistant General Secretary
of the French Foreign Ministry, Claude Martin, to Cambodia's First
Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh during their meeting in the
latter's residence in Aix-en-Provence, southeast France, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
France has also expressed to Cambodia's Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen its wish for a halt of hostilities, the resumption without
delay of the normal functioning of government institutions, and
the respect for the constitutional principles adopted by Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The French government Monday urged a "return of the law" in
Cambodia, after troops loyal to Hun Sen ousted the troops of
Ranariddh from Phnom Penh on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
France has called on the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to "use their influence upon different sides of Cambodia"
to seek an end to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN countries, which include Thailand, Malaysia,
Singapore, Indonesia, the Philippines and Brunei, today expressed
regret over the violence that took place in Cambodia over the past
several days and called for an immediate ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh will go to the United States on Wednesday to meet
with U.S. officials and United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
