<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Report: Aid Insufficient to Meet Iraq's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A report by the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNCICEF) has said aid supplies fall short of
meeting Iraq's actual needs and warned of deteriorating health
status in Iraq, local newspaper the Baghdad Observer reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report released last week by UNICEF's Executive Council's
12th ordinary session said that aid supplies offered by the
U.N. agency to Iraq are unsufficient even if they are offered at
appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF has funded most of the children's health programs
in Iraq since the Gulf War in 1991. But it cut its activities in
the country after the Iraqi-U.N. "oil-for-food" deal came into
force last December.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Iraq can sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over six months on a renewable basis for the purchase of
humanitarian goods urgently needed in the country, which has
been under harsh U.N.-imposed sanctions for nearly seven years
after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
From its oil revenues, Iraq has earmarked 210 million dollars
for medical supplies and another 10 million dollars for health
repairs. However, only a small part of the medical supplies
bought by Iraq under the "oil-for-food" deal has arrived the
country up till now.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the U.N. agency was accused of being
indifferent to Iraq's needs which are submitted by Iraq's Health
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In March, the UNICEF and Iraq's Health Ministry launched a
country-wide campaign to immunize more than 3 million Iraqi
children against polio.
</P>
<P>
Figures published by the Iraqi Health Ministry indicated that
U.N. sanctions have made the death toll of the Iraqis ever year
rise from about 30,000 before 1991 to 140,000 now.
</P>
<P>
World Health Organization (WHO) warned earlier that Iraq's
health system is close to collapse.
</P>
<P>
Government drug warehouses and pharmacies have few stocks of
medicines and medical supplies, WHO said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's External Trade Up in 1st 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's external trade grew
slightly in the first four months of this year as compared with
the same period of 1996, according to official statistics issued
here today.
</P>
<P>
The volume of Hong Kong's re-exports increased by 6.2 percent,
but the volume of domestic exports decreased by 3.3 percent in the
January-April period of 1997 against the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Taken together, the volume of total exports grew by 4.7
percent, while the imports grew by 6.6 percent in volume.
</P>
<P>
Comparing April of this year with April of 1996, the volume of
domestic exports of footwear increased significantly by 106
percent, the Census and Statistics Department said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the volume of domestic exports of radios of all
kinds, textile made-ups and related articles, travel goods,
handbags and similar articles decreased sharply, by 80 percent, 69
percent and 49 percent respectively, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
