<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SFOR to Remain in Bosnia and Herzegovina Till Next June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) leaders reaffirmed here today that the
NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) will remain in Bosnia and
Herzegovina till next June.
</P>
<P>
They also called on the authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina
to accelerate the implementation of the 1995 Bosnia Peace
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"While SFOR's mandate comes to an end in June 1998, we have a
commitment to and a long-term interest in stability in Bosnia and
Herzegovina and the surrounding region," NATO heads of state and
government said in a special declaration issued after a luncheon
at the two-day summit in the Spanish capital of Madrid.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders called on the parties to the Peace Agreement,
signed on December 14, 1995 in Paris after it had been negotiated
in Dayton, Ohio, "to comply fully with the commitments they
themselves have agreed and to implement the Peace Agreement
without delay".
</P>
<P>
"The authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina should be in no
doubt that there can be no military option for any party or ethnic
group now or in the future," they insisted.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR of 31,000-strong troops was activated on December 20,
1996, when the one-year mandate of its predecessor, the
Implementation Force (IFOR), expired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
