<HEADLINE> Philippines, Bangladesh to Expand Trade Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine and Bangladeshi trade
officials have agreed to expand trade and economic cooperation
between the two countries by amending the existing bilateral trade
accord.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautista and his
Bangladeshi counterpart, Commerce and Industry Minister Toafel
Ahmed reached the agreement at the second meeting of the
Philippines-Bangladesh Joint Trade Committee which ended here
today.
</P>
<P>
Both delegations agreed in principle to amend the bilateral
trade agreement which was signed in 1980 to align it with current
international trading rules and practices and to include in its
coverage trade in services.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
to conclude an Investment Promotion and Protection Agreement in
the very near future.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Philippine delegation expressed keen
interest to cooperate with Bangladesh in oil and gas exploration,
military hardware, public transportation and pharmaceutical
industries.
</P>
<P>
Bangladeshi officials stressed that it welcomes Philippine
involvement in these areas and participation in its economic
development.
</P>
<P>
They said Bangladesh wants cooperation with the Philippines in
the areas of trade, agriculture and agri-business, science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by private sector representatives
from both countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
