<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Azerbaijan Defends Oil Contract with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Azerbaijani Foreign Ministry
today refuted a Turkmen protest against the Russian-Azerbaijani
contract on the Kyapaz oil field in the Caspina Sea, reported the
Interfax News Service.
</P>
<P>
"Such statements cannot have any influence on the
Russian-Azerbaijani agreement signed in Moscow," Azerbaijani
Foreign Minister Gasan Gasanov.
</P>
<P>
Gasanov said that his country was always ready to give a
positive response to constructive Turkmen proposals for
cooperation in the development of offshore oil fields.
</P>
<P>
These proposals remain valid, he continued, and Azerbaijan
"intends to discuss any beneficial proposals with fraternal
Turkmenistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-Azerbaijani agreement on joint development of the
Kyapaz oil field was signed on Friday during Azerbaijani President
Geidar Aliyev's visit to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The Turkmen Foreign Ministry lodged a protest Saturday over the
the contract signed between the Kyapaz offshore field by Russia's
Lukoil and Rosneft oil companies and the State Oil Company of the
Azerbaijani Republic (SOCAR).
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan demanded categorically that this agreement be
annulled in order to avoid consequences for which Turkmenistan
"will bear no responsibility."
</P>
<P>
"Turkmenistan could only welcome such cooperation if the
Serdar field (the former promezhutochnoye field) which belongs to
Turkmenistan and is referred to in the agreement as Kyapaz had not
been included in the zone of joint development operations (between
the Russian and Azerbaijani companies)," the Turkmen ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian-Azerbaijani agreement, SOCAR will have a 50
percent stake in the project, Lukoil a 30 percent stake and
Rosneft a 20 percent stake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
