<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebel Rejects Mediator in Talks With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking official of the rebel
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today said the suspended
peace talks in the southern Philippines does not need a third
party or a mediator to resume.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, also
described as "insignificant" the role Muslim Mindanao Governor Nur
Misuari will play if he decided to mediate in the impasse under
the directive of President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Misuari, the rebel-turned-governor, said in his state-of-the-
region address on Monday that he was ready to mediate "for the
sake of peace in Mindanao."
</P>
<P>
"He is our brother, he is welcome in Mindanao," Jaafar said in
an interview with the local television ABS-CBN referring to
Misuari.
</P>
<P>
"But the lack of a mediator is not our problem here," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar also said the government must have misread the message
and erroneously believed that the solution to the impasse is a
broker.
</P>
<P>
Ramos today ordered government troops in Mindanao to cease from
conducting offensive actions against the MILF in order to allow
government negotiators to talk with rebel leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The bottom line here is sincerity. Both sides must be
sincere," Jaafar noted.
</P>
<P>
"The MILF is sincere. The government, it appears, is not," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Asked what would bring the MILF back to the negotiating table,
Jaafar said the government must stop the "massive and all-out
military operations against our forces here in Central Mindanao
first." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
