<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Expects 5.3 Billion Dollars from CGI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia expects 5.3 billion U.S.
dollars in new foreign loans this year from the Consultative Group
on Indonesia (CGI) despite a possible reduction in aid from Japan,
a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Official news agency Antara today quoted Coordinating Minister
for Economy and Finance Saleh Afiff as saying that Indonesia
expected the CGI, which will hold its annual meeting in Tokyo
early next week, to give at least the same amount as last year.
</P>
<P>
The CGI committed 5.26 billion U.S. dollars in new loans and
grants last year, compared to 5.358 billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
Afiff said that Japan -- CGI's largest creditor -- was facing
financial problems which had forced it to reduce its foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Japan's foreign aid to Indonesia through the CGI was 1.917
billion dollars last year or 36 percent of the total, as compared
to 2.14 billion dollars or 40 percent of the total in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
The CGI groups the United States, Australia, Austria, Belgium,
Denmark, Finland, Britain, Italy, Japan, Germany, Canada, South
Korea, Norway, France, New Zealand, Spain, Switzerland, Sweden and
some international monetary organizations including the World
Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
