<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Leaves for Nairobi to Attend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Hassan
Ahmed al-Bashir left here today for Kenya, heading the Sudanese
delegation for the summit of Inter-Governmental Authority on
Drought and Development (IGADD).
</P>
<P>
The IGADD organization groups Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia
Eritrea, Djibouti and Somali.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Mustafa Osman
Ismail announced that the Sudanese delegation would brief the
summit, due to be held in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi, on the
Khartoum peace agreement signed last April between the Sudanese
government and two groups of the rebel movement in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
John Garang, leader of the mainstream rebel group in southern
Sudan, is expected to participate in the IGADD summit, which is
due to discuss the issue of achieving peace in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources here, there has been a
prolonged debate on how to listen to the views of John Garang, who
will most probably express them at a closed session.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Garang's presence at the summit will be a
positive step on the road to continuing the dialog between the
Sudanese government and the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese delegation to the summit also includes Riyak
Mashar, a prominent rebel leader who has signed a peace agreement
with the government in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Nairobi, Mashar said he was ready to meet
Garang and persuade him to join the peace march.
</P>
<P>
A number of Sudanese officials have expressed optimism about
the outcome of the IGADD summit, especially in case of the
participation of Garang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
