<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de France Riders Blood Tested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- International Cycling Union (UCI)
officials blood tested several riders before the start of
Tuesday's third stage in the Tour de France cycle race. They were
all allowed to start, according to reports from Vire.
</P>
<P>
The officials tested for Erythropoietin, or EPO, which boosts
the red blood cells which carry oxygen around the body.
</P>
<P>
The UCI said the eight riders who have failed tests this year
should not be branded cheats.
</P>
<P>
Riders whose blood has an oxygen-carrying capacity of above 50
percent are deemed unfit to race and automatically suspended on
health grounds because of the risk of blood clots or heart, brain
and kidney damage caused by thickened blood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
