<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activities in Northeast China Commemorate Anti-Japanese War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China's Liaoning Province has been
holding activities recently for the 60th anniversary of the
outbreak of the War of Resistance Against Japan on July 7, 1937.
</P>
<P>
Many people have visited memorials and museums in the
provincial capital, a local official said.
</P>
<P>
The Shenyang Museum for the September 18 Incident, an important
national patriotic education center, has had about 900,000
visitors in the past six years, and mementos of the "Pingding
Mountain Massacre" in Fushun have become an important way to help
people think about the past, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Recently, various meetings have been held to commemorate events
in Liaoning, the first province in China to be captured by
Japanese troops and the first to rise in resistance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday morning, the Shenyang Municipal Committee of the
Communist Party of China held a forum to mark the 60th anniversary
of the Marco Polo Bridge Incident.
</P>
<P>
"More than 20 million Chinese died during the war and the
Chinese people fought hard for victory," said Han Ao, former
deputy-chief of staff of the Shenyang Military Area Command.
</P>
<P>
"Today, we resumed the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong
without using any force, because China has become stronger now,"
he said. "This means a country is bound to be humiliated if it is
weak."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
