<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-fire Monitors Call for Self-Restraint by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A five-nation group monitoring a
cease-fire in south Lebanon today called on Israeli occupation
forces and Lebanese guerrilla of Hezbollah, which are involved in
a war of friction in south Lebanon, to maintain self-refrainment.
</P>
<P>
However, the international panel failed to blame either side
for the escalation of the Arab-Israeli conflict on the last
active battlefront in the past few days, in which nearly a dozen
of Lebanese civilians were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises the United States, Israel,
France, Syria and Lebanon, currently headed by U.S. diplomat
David Greenly, started a meeting on Monday morning to discuss two
complaints filed by the Lebanese government and the other two
by Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued following their meeting in the south
Lebanese border town of Naqoura, representatives from the five
nations, also urged the fighting sides to totally comply with
the cease-fire understanding reached between Lebanon and Israel
in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese complaints lodged on July 3 and July 7 said
Israeli artillery intentionally targeted civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued this morning, the cease-fire monitoring
committee said it "accepted as factual" that the Israeli
shelling had caused injuries.
</P>
<P>
"The Lebanese delegate stated that the firing was far from
the area of military conflict ... and that Israeli targeting of
civilians has become routine," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Israeli delegate claimed that the
bombardment "was conducted in self-defense", according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the Israeli complaints filed on July 3 and July 6,
the committee also "accepted as factual" that at least one 120mm
mortar and one 122mm Katyusha rocket had impacted on Israel. It
noted that neither attacks caused injuries.
</P>
<P>
This was the 13th meeting of the committee since this
year. Many Lebanese have doubted about the panel's effectiveness
in monitoring the cease-fire in light of the repeated
low-profile statements it has issued since its establishment in
August 1996 under the "April understanding."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese army sources said that two Katyusha rockets hit
northern Israel on Sunday night after they were apparently
targeted on the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Israeli-client militia, South Lebanon Army
(SLA), claimed that seven rockets landed in Israel on the
outskirts of the coastal town of Nahayiey.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, confirmed today
that two of its fighters were killed Monday in action against
Israeli forces and the SLA.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by Hezbollah in Beirut identified the two
members as Mohsen Abdullah Fneigh and Mahmoud Hussein Salman, but
it did not specify. "They were martyred when performing their
holy struggle duties on July 7," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite Muslim Hezbollah spearheads a guerrilla warfare in
a bid to oust Israeli occupation forces from the Lebanese land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
