<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Overseas Seminar Participants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met here
today with overseas representatives participating in the ongoing
Transcultural Seminar on Economic Development and International
Exchanges in the Asia-Pacific Region Into the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Li welcomed the politicians, entrepreneurs and academic
personnel from Japan, the United States, Canada and Germany to
participate in the seminar and hoped that it would make positive
contributions to enhancing mutual understanding and promoting
friendly cooperation among Asia-Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
Mankind is at a crucial point in moving toward another century,
Li said. He stressed that all countries should give answers to
such challenges and issues as how to establish a stable and
peaceful international environment, how to make sure that all
countries can enjoy equal rights in international affairs, how to
establish a new type of international economic order featuring
mutual benefit, complementarity and common development, how to
jointly abide by the principles of mutual non-interference in
international affairs and respect for the wishes of the people of
all countries in choosing their own development road in line with
their own conditions, and how to manage effective international
cooperation to deal with the issues of environmental protection
and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the East and Northeast Asian regions should
maintain their momentum of economic growth while adapting
themselves to the rapid development of science and technology, Li
noted.
</P>
<P>
As a country of the Asian-Pacific region, China pursues its
independent foreign policy of peace and has always attached
importance to its exchanges and cooperation with Asian-Pacific
countries, devoting itself wholeheartedly to both regional and
global peace and stability, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Teruyuki Akema, chairman of the Japanese Association for the
Communication of Transcultural Studies, said, on behalf of the
overseas participants at the seminar, that he fully agreed with
what Premier Li said. All countries should take new steps to greet
the 21st century, he added. The seminar, focusing on the prospects
in the 21st century, bears important significance as it is being
held in China, which is a country playing an extremely important
role in the region and in the world as a whole, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
