<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Tumble at Close on Weak Gold Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nervous investors continued to
sell out of gold stocks dragging the Australian share market to a
lower close today.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index tumbled 33.8 points to 2,679.2, its
lowest close since June 18, after hitting an intra-day low of
2,668.8.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dived for the third day in a row, losing 6.44
percent or 82.2 points to end at 1,193.3, the index's lowest level
since March 26, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed in Sydney at 318.25 US dollars, down one US
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Senior broker Bill Richmond said that "at the end of the day,
the gold sector is down and it has dragged down the all
ordinaries."
</P>
<P>
The all resources index ended down 40 points at 1,431.0, while
the all industrials index was down 30.1 points at 4,284.7.
</P>
<P>
In the bank sector, Commonwealth Bank dropped 22.9 cents to
15.74, with analysts saying the lower margins in home lending
interest rates had affected its share price.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Bank lost three cents to 9.80 Australian dollars, and
Westpac Bank slipped five cents to 7.84.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 503.67 million shares traded and valued
at 1.12 billion Australian dollars (834.4 million US dollars),
with rises of 364 outnumbering falls of 121.  
</P>
</TEXT>
