<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Calls on International Community to Condemn Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's First Prime Minister
Norodom Ranariddh today called on the international community to
condemn the "coup d'etat" staged by Hun Sen, the country's second
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
During a press conference in Paris today, Ranariddh called on
the international community, the United Nations, the signing
countries of the 1991 Paris peace agreements on Cambodia, the
European Union and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) "never to recognize a regime resulting from a coup d'etat."
</P>
<P>
"I demand all countries to condemn the criminal and bloody coup
d'etat, and to insisit that any solution should conform to the
Paris agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would go to Washington and New York on Wednesday to
meet with U.S. officials and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
while Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot will go to ASEAN
countries to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said that resistance is being organized in the
western part of Cambodia under the control of royalist forces, and
that he keeps telephone contact with his generals in the field.
</P>
<P>
He also said he himself would go back to Cambodia to head
the resistance.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a resistance inside the country and the chief
of the resistance should be inside the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is reportedly going on in Siem Reap, 314 kilometers
north of the capital Phnom Penh and near the 12th century
historical site of Angkor Temples, between the royalist forces and
the troops of Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said that he would go to Thailand first, and that his
return to Cambodia "would be conditioned by the attitude of
Thailand, which seems to adopt an attitude of neutrality."
</P>
<P>
He denied that he would establish a military alliance with the
Khmer Rouge guerrillas, who have for their part called for a
people's uprising against Hun Sen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
