<HEADLINE> ASEAN Calls for Immediate Ceasefire in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (xinhua) -- The seven-member Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today urged rival groups in
Cambodia to stop fighting immediately and resolve their
differences peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN calls for an immediate ceasefire," Malaysian Foreign
Minister and Chairman of the ASEAN Standing Committee Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi said today in a statement on behalf of the regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said that ASEAN was dismayed and deeply regretted the
unfortunate turn of events in Cambodia resulting in the loss of
innocent lives of both Cambodian citizens and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam, called on Cambodia's two
co-prime ministers Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Hun Sen to resolve
their differences peacefully, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Cambodian people have suffered from conflict for the past
two decades. It would be tragic for the conflict to re-ignite in
the country that has long suffered from war," Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN also urged the Government of Cambodia to take immediate
steps to ensure the safety of foreign nationals and provide
protection for their properties in that country.
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN would monitor the situation in Cambodia and
convene a special meeting of ASEAN Foreign Ministers in Kuala
Lumpur on Thursday to review the situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from Cambodia's capital Phnom Penh said Hun
Sen has taken control of the capital during weekend fighting
against supporters of Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Phnom Penh was reported to have calmed down.
</P>
</TEXT>
