<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Take Best Course of Action on Cambodia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) will take the "best course of action" on
Cambodia's scheduled entry later this month into the regional
grouping, Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said
today.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers will meet in Kuala Lumpur on Thursday
to discuss the latest political situation in Cambodia, Abdullah
told the Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN consists of Brunei, Indoensia, Malaysia, Singapore,
the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
"Of course during the meeting, we will seek views of ASEAN
members and take the very best course of action," he said,
refusing to elaborate on Thursday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim asked the Foreign
Ministry today to study with its ASEAN counterparts the
possibility of a change in ASEAN's stand on admitting Cambodia
into the regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said although ASEAN is sticking to the original schedule
for Cambodia's admission, Malaysia has to study the latest
development in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers decided in Kuala Lumpur on May 31
to admit Cambodia, along with Laos and Myanmar, into the regional
grouping during the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting scheduled for
July 24-25.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Monday that Cambodia would definitely be accepted
into ASEAN at the end of the month together with Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Cambodia is gradually returning to normal
after fierce fighting between troops of co-prime ministers Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and Hun Sen, which claimed 15 lives. 
</P>
