<HEADLINE> Egypt's New Ministers Take Oath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's new ministers, having
survived the limited cabinet reshuffle, took the constitutional
oath before President Hosni Mubarak at the presidency headquarters
today.
</P>
<P>
Ten newly-appointed ministers were sworn in at the ceremony,
attended by Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri and Chief of the
Presidential Cabinet Zakaria Azmi.
</P>
<P>
Four of them are new comers in the one-and-half-year-old
cabinet which has remained intact since Ganzouri took office in
January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mufeed Shihab, Rector of Cairo University, was assigned the
post of minister of higher education and minister of state for
scientific research affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Abdel Halim Abu Zeid, chairman of the Water Resources
Conservation Research Center, will head the Ministry of Public
Works and Water Resources to replace the late Abdel-Hadi Radi who
died last November.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassadress to Japan Mervat el-Talawi takes charge of
the Ministry of Insurances and Social Affairs, and Nadia Riyad
Makram, who was in charge of Women and Development at the U.N.
Development Program, took the post of minister of environment
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members with the key portfolios -- Defense Minister
Mohamed Hussein Tantawi, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Interior
Minister Hassan el-Alfy -- remain in their jobs. The personnel
shift will take in two women, one short of the original cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Others that assumed new ministerial portfolios and took the
constitutional oath are old faces.
</P>
<P>
Atef Ebeid, who currently takes charge of the Public Sector as
well as Administrative Development and Environment, was nominated
minister of public enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Youssef Boutros-Ghali, minister of state at the Cabinet, who
cut short his week-long trip to London and returned home this
morning, was assigned the heavy-weight economic portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Zafer al-Beshry, steering the Ministry of Planning at the
moment, becomes the minister of State for planning and
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Abu-Amer, the current Minister for People's Assembly
and Shura Council Affairs, turns out to be the new minister of
state for administrative development.
</P>
<P>
While Mahmoud Sherif, Minister of Local Government, was trusted
to lead the newly-installed Ministry of Rural Development, Hussein
Kamel Bahaa Eddine managed to keep the portfolio of education.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak later held a meeting with the ministerial body. Absent
from the meeting were Information Minister Safwat el-Sherif,
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili, and Minister of Finance
Mohi Eddin el-Gharib, who are all abroad.
</P>
<P>
The nominations were made this morning during a consultation
session held by Ganzouri with these new appointees.
</P>
<P>
Rumors about injecting new blood to the one-year-old cabinet
have been rife since the beginning of this year. No new members
have joined the 32-member cabinet since Ganzouri took office in
January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
