<HEADLINE> Prime Minister's Rate Comments Push Dollar Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Prime minister John Howard's
desire for lower interest rate today sent the Australian dollar
down to levels not seen in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 74.22 US cents from 74.46 late
yesterday, after trading in a range of 74.14 to 74.52 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Townsville this afternoon, the prime minister said
he would like to see interest rates lower, "one of the reasons why
interest rates have come down in the country is that we are no
longer running such large budget deficits", he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian market had been "a little short" when Howard's
comments were made, the currency would remain under pressure from
interest rate concerns, said the National Australia Bank's manager
of foreign exchange trading Mike Eastaway.
</P>
<P>
The slid of gold prices, which pushed the Australian dollar
lower yesterday, slowed slightly today, closing at 318.25 US
dollars per ounce after recording a four dollars fall yesterday.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rate, the Australian dollar finished at 83.94 from
83.73 against the yen and it was at 1.3016 from 1.3017 against the
mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
