<HEADLINE> Lewis Supports Stockholm Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nine times Olympic champion Carl
Lewis of the United States has joined a group of elite athletes
pledging public support for the Stockholm 2004 Olympic bid.
</P>
<P>
The athletes, headed by former world triple jump record holder
Willie Banks and former Wimbledon champion Stefan Edberg, believe
Stockholm would provide the best facilities and environment for
the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Stockholm, Rome, Athens, Cape Town and Buenos Aires are on the
final shortlist of cities bidding to host the Games. The
International Olympic Committee (IOC) will choose the winning city
in Lausanne on September 5.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, who anchored the Santa Monica Track Club quartet to
victory in Monday's Stockholm Grand Prix, told a news conference
on Tuesday he had visited each of the bidding cities.
</P>
<P>
"I am supporting this bid because I know this community," Lewis
said. "I knew this community before the Olympics was an issue."
</P>
<P>
Banks said: "We want the world to know that the best city for
the athletes will be Stockholm," Banks said.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the athletes said a committee, called the
International Athletes' Council, had been formed to support the
bid, comprising 53 athletes from around the world in 22 Olympic
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
The statement said: "We, the athletes of the Council, have
compared the perfect weather in Stockholm, the clean air and water
and believe these factors all support the victory for Stockholm
2004." 
</P>
</TEXT>
