<HEADLINE> Chittagong Labor Dispute to be Arbitrated in 15 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The stalemate in Chittagong port came
to an end this afternoon as rival unions agreed to submit their
dispute to arbitration by the Shipping Ministry, said official
news agency Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS).
</P>
<P>
The six-day deadlock came to an end following a fruitful
meeting between Deputy Minister for Shipping Nath Shambu and
representatives of concerned organizations, including the Merchant
Workers' Union and the Coaster Hatch Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 merchant workers started the strike Thursday
afternoon in protest against engagement of hatch workers in
lighterage of cargo from ships anchored at the outer anchorage,
claiming they were supposed to that job.
</P>
<P>
The hatch workers, however, said that they were driven out from
their work by the merchant workers by force in 1986 and they were
struggling for the last few years to get back their right.
</P>
<P>
It was unanimously decided at the meeting that the Ministry of
Shipping will take decision regarding this dispute in the next 10
to 15 days while workers will maintain a status quo till the
decision comes from the ministry, the BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
Port officials said that the striking workers have already
resumed their duties and full-length operation activities are
going on.
</P>
<P>
The Strike has forced over 30 ships including nine ships at the
outer anchorage stranded, creating congestion in this country's
commercial lifeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
