<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Summit Opens in Madrid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) began its two-day summit, which was described
by its Secretary General Javier Solana as a "defining moment" for
a new NATO here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the summit, Solana said, "We
will open the doors of this Alliance to the first new members from
Central and Eastern Europe."
</P>
<P>
"We will create new opportunities for co-operation and
partnership, that will enhance the security of all nations in the
Euro-Atlantic area. And we will pursue our efforts to make NATO's
structures ready to face the challenges of the 21st century,"
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new NATO would be as indispensable to the
Europe of tomorrow as it was to the Europe of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"Our meeting today and tomorrow with our partners will
demonstrate that we will enter the next century in a spirit of
solidarity and confidence."
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the participants, Spanish President of the Government
(prime minister) Jose Maria Aznar said, "We want peace, and it is
expected of us that we guarantee it. We must provide a response to
the security problems that affect our fellow citizens in the
current international context."
</P>
<P>
"Spain is honored to belong to NATO and offers its warmest
hospitality to all the participants in the summit," said Aznar.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his country had decided to take necessary
steps to fully participate in the alliance's new command structure.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government of the 16 NATO members,
representatives of the Western European Union and the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe were present at today's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, they will be joined by representatives from
members of NATO's Partnership for Peace (PfP) program. They are
Albania, Armenia, Austria, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bulgaria, the
Czech Republic, Estonia, Finland, Georgia, Hungary, Kazakhstan,
Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovakia,
Slovenia, Sweden, Switzerland, Macedonia, Turkmenistan, Ukraine,
and Uzbekistan. Malta ceased to be a PfP last year.
</P>
<P>
Albania, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary,
Latvia, Lithuania, Poland, Romania, Slovakia, Slovenia and
Macedonia - have applied for NATO membership. Of them, the Czech
Republic, Hungary and Poland are expected to be invited to join
NATO at the end of the Summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
