<HEADLINE> China, Indonesia Pledge to Strengthen Economic Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China and Indonesia today pledged
to strengthen their economic cooperation on the basis of equal and
mutual beneficial principle.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the fourth session of the
Joint Commission on Economic, Trade and Technical Cooperation
between the Governments of China and Indonesia, Indonesian Trade
and Industry Minister Tunky Ariwibowo and Vice Minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation of China Li Guohua said the
prospect of the economic cooperation between the two countries is
very bright.
</P>
<P>
They said the economic relations could be developed speedily as
long as both sides make efforts to remove all the obstacles in the
cooperation process.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held that there are ample opportunities to expand
the bilateral trade which had increased to 3.78 billion US dollars
in 1996 from 2.69 billion dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia now is the 15th biggest trade partner of China in the
world and the second in the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) countries.
</P>
<P>
To promote the development of investment, the two sides also
expressed the hope that the two countries will soon arrive at an
agreement on the avoidance of double taxation.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral trade after the return of Hong Kong to China,
Tunky expected that Indonesia's exports to China through Hong Kong
will be increased considering Hong Kong's position as Asia's
leading center for commerce and finance.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li Guohua also put forth many proposals to
strengthen the economic cooperation between the two sides, such as
in the fields of energy, fishery, banking, investment and trade.
</P>
<P>
The session will end on Wednesday. The joint commission, which
was established in 1990, held its third session in Beijing at the
end of 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
