<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri formed a new cabinet this morning by reshuffling his
one-and-half-year-old government.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members with the key portfolios -- Defense Minister
Mohammed Hussein Tantawi, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Interior
Minister Hassan el-Alfy -- remain in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported today that
Ganzouri met several incumbent cabinet members this morning who
are expected either to be assigned to new posts or give up their
jobs, as well as his new appointees.
</P>
<P>
According to MENA, Rector of Cairo University Mufeed Shihab
will take over the Higher Education and Scientific Research
Ministry from Venus Gouda.
</P>
<P>
Mahmud Abu Zeid, chairman of the Water Resources Conservation
Research Center, will take up the office of minister of public
works and water resources, which was held by Abdel-Hadi Radi until
he died on the post last November.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Youssef Boutros-Gahli,
who cut short his week-long trip to London and was summoned back
home Monday night, will be appointed as minister of economy to
replace Nawal el-Tatawi.
</P>
<P>
Minister for People's Assembly and Shura Council Affairs
Mohammed Abu-Amer will take up the post of minister of state for
administrative development.
</P>
<P>
Zafer el-Beshri retained his post as minister of state for
planning and international cooperation, while Hussein Bahaa Eddine
managed to keep the portfolio of education.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Sherif, Minister of Local Government was nominated to
head the newly-installed Ministry of Rural Development.
</P>
<P>
As the three incumbent female ministers are destined to lose
their jobs, another two women step in.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassadress to Japan Mervat el-Talawi will become
minister of insurances and social affairs; Nadia Makram Ebeid, who
was in charge of Women and Development at the U.N. Development
Program, seemed to be the choice for the post of minister of
environment affairs.
</P>
<P>
Rumors about injecting new blood to the one-year-old cabinet
have been rife since the beginning of this year. No new members
have joined the 32-member cabinet since Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri took office in January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
