<HEADLINE> HKMA To Issue Post-handover Exchange Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) will hold a tender for Exchange Fund Notes on Monday, the
first after the handover, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The notes to be tendered belong to the 16th issue of three-year
Exchange Fund Notes under the Exchange Fund Notes issue program
which was introduced in 1991, the English-language South China
Morning Post said.
</P>
<P>
Similar to previous issues, an amount of 500 million HK dollars
(64.1 million US dollars) in three-year notes will be on offer.
</P>
<P>
Another 100 million HK dollars (12.8 million US dollars) will
be issued and held as reserve by the HKMA, the de facto central
bank in Hong Kong, to adjust demand and supply through qualified
market-makers in the secondary market.
</P>
<P>
The notes will mature on July 17, 2000, with an annual interest
rate of 6.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to latest statistics, the total amount of Exchange
Fund Notes outstanding until the end of May was 97.45 billion HK
dollars (12.5 billion US dollars). The average daily turnover of
those notes in that month was 29.6 billion HK dollars (3.8 billion
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exchange Fund Notes represent one of the most important market
tools the HKMA uses to stabilize the local currency market and
interbank lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
