<HEADLINE> Petition for Charter Changes Dismissed in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Charter changes advocates in the
Philippines today received another heavy blow after the seven
members of the Commission on Elections unanimously voted against a
petition calling for Constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
A 14-page resolution signed by the seven commissioners said
that, in accordance with the ruling of the Supreme Court, the
Commission dismissed at bench the petition filed on June 23 by the
People's Initiative for Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA).
</P>
<P>
The resolution said no hearing would be scheduled to determine
the sufficiency of the petition, and the commission would not
order its election officers to verify the 5.5 million signatures
the PIRMA submitted to the Commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission also asked the PIRMA to retrieve all the files
and the signatures within five days, saying that it would not
assume responsibility for the safe keeping of these files upon the
expiration of the period granted.
</P>
<P>
The country's Supreme Court has ruled for the second time
against charter changes that would lift the term limits for
President Fidel Ramos and other incumbent officials and
congressmen.
</P>
<P>
But advocates of charter changes are not reconciled to defeat.
After the court made its decision, the PIRMA filed its petition
which called for a plebiscite to change the Charter.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos said he would step down as his term ends next
June. But meanwhile, he admitted that he was facing mounting
pressure from supporters who favor him staying in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
