<HEADLINE> Ten Kenyans Died in Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The death toll reached 10 during
violent confrontations between the police and opposition
supporters in Kenya on monday, a local report said today.
</P>
<P>
Among the 10 killed were one student and a policeman.
</P>
<P>
Scores of people, including three opposition parliament
members, were seriously injured in the capital Nairobi, where
most shops were closed on the day and many barricaded against
looters.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has voiced strong condemnation on the
nationwide disturbance.
</P>
<P>
"The government will deal firmly with those found to be
inciting others to violence, looting or destruction of property,"
warned a government statement issued Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"Changes will always come and go but a culture of violence and
lawlessness should not be nurtured in our nation as it may easily
take root and destroy our stability, undermine security and all
our national achievements and aspirations," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Joseph Kamotho, Secretary General of the Ruling Kenya
African National Union (KANU), said the tragedy is "a conspiracy
by the opposition to seize political power by force," charging the
opposition with attempting to unleash chaos so as to make the
general election impossible.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leaders and some church groups had called the
so-called Saba Saba (July 7 in Swahili) rallies in some 50 towns
in the eastern African country, disregarding the banning order
from the government and its warning of breaking-up.
</P>
<P>
They claimed the rallies were designed to press for
constitutional reforms and direct dialogue between the government
and the opposition before the general elections whose date is yet
to be fixed. 
</P>
