<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Living Plant Discovered in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A leading botanist has said the
world's oldest living plant has been discovered in the Tasmanian
wilderness in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Stephen Harris, chief of the Tasmanian Parks and Wildlife
Service, said tests indicated the Lomatia tasmanica (Lomatia
tasmanica), commonly known as King's Holly, was 43,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
The plant, found in a one square kilometer patch of rainforest
in Tasmania's south-western World Heritage Area, was originally
found in the 1930s but its age had never been suspected, Dr.
Harris was quoted today by the Australian Associated Press (AAP)
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It's a wonderful creation to be able to study," Dr. Harris
said.
</P>
<P>
Botanists previously thought the world's oldest living plant
was a 13,000-year-old United States huckleberry. The oldest tree
is an Arizona bristle-cone pine, dated at a youthful 4,700 years
of age.
</P>
<P>
The Tasmanian plant was a self-propagating clone, which meant
it did not produce seeds but reproduced by shedding "cuttings" of
itself onto the forest floor which grew into genetically identical
clones.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Harris said the plant looked like it consisted of several
hundred individual shrubs but research had shown they were all
genetically identical, meaning they were essentially the same
plant.
</P>
<P>
Cuttings from the plant were identical to fossilized remains in
the forest floor carbon-dated at 43,000 years, according to AAP.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Harris said the plant had glossy, pointed leaves resembling
holly and flowered regularly, which was unusual for a plant that
did not seed.
</P>
<P>
He said after studying the plant's ecology and chromosomes,
scientists hoped it could eventually be reproduced and sold to
gardeners.
</P>
<P>
A cutting had lived for years in a pot at the Royal Tasmanian
Botanical Gardens, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Trade Deficit with Japan Tripples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's trade deficit with Japan
more than trippled last year from 44.4 million U.S. dollars in
1995 to 143.7 million although total trade witnessed a big
increase, the local press Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Nigeria's trade with Japan amounted to 476.7 million
U.S. Dollars, compared with 313.8 million in the previous year,
the local newspaper said, quoting a release from the Japan
External Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the country's exports to Japan rose by 23.6
percent from 134.7 million dollars to 166.5 million, while
imports from Japan reached 310.2 million dollars, a sharp rise
from the previous year's 179.1 million.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, crude oil accounted for 95.2 percent
of Nigeria's exports to Japan to 158.5 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the non-oil exports, sesame seed gained 6.9 million
dollars, accounting for 82.3 percent f non-oil earnings from
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's export of cocoa beans, which penetrated the Japanese
market for the first time in 1995, fell from 100,000 dollars last
year from the previous year's 300,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other non-oil commodities, including tropical wood, ornamental
fish and bones and horn cores, each fetched 100,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports from Japan last year mainly include iron and steel,
trucks and buses, pumps and engines, cars and motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have attributed Nigeria's improved trade
relations with Japan to the government's desperate search for
alternative trade partners as its major traditional trade
partners in the West impose some sanctions on it over its alleged
slow pace to democratic rule and human rights abuse record.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has since 1995 begun to turn to Asia, Pacific and
Latin America for more economic and trade activities as a
counterpoise to the sanctions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0175 </DOCNO>
