<HEADLINE> South Korea to Fight Against School Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
urged today to eradicate school violence by all means after a
recent string of increasingly serious violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
Deaths, suicides and violent beating have resulted over the
past few months from organized school bullying and intimidation
activities.
</P>
<P>
There are hundreds of organized juvenile delinquent groups
operating across the country, and violence has affected both high
and middle schools, including girls' schools, said the Home
Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Police apprehended 913 teenagers involved in 106 organized
delinquent criminal groups during the first half of this year, of
whom 327 were arrested.
</P>
<P>
School violence has reached alarming level, said Prime Minister
Koh Kun last weekend, calling on the police, parents and teachers
to make a concerted effort to ward off violence in and around
school.
</P>
<P>
Kim asked the government to improve education and other systems
to uproot school violence, adding that the school violence should
be handled by the whole society.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Home Affair Ministry has set up a special task
force to deal with the problem and ordered nationwide crackdown on
juvenile delinquents.
</P>
<P>
Some 13,427 policemen, teachers and civic group members have
been mobilized to keep order at 7,784 schools, private libraries
and learning institutions across the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also plans to increase the number of policemen
patrolling the 4,634 schools nationwide to 10,235. 
</P>
</TEXT>
