<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Coal Producer Improving In Continued Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Technical upgrading and market
competition are expected to help China's money-losing coal
industry to show a profit by the end of this year, according to a
source at the Ministry of Coal Industry.
</P>
<P>
The Yanzhou Coal Mining Group Co. Ltd. in east China's Shandong
Province, which was one of the key state coal producers but which
has been debt-ridden since the 1980s, has set an example for these
mines nationwide.
</P>
<P>
With the central government's relaxing of coal price controls,
the company was brought in line with the market, and set up new
development guidelines: concentrating on coal cutting while
putting equal stress on coal cutting and other non-coal
undertakings.
</P>
<P>
The group separated the coal cutting and dressing from other
undertakings, a usual international practice. Beginning from 1993,
the group organized efforts to improve the fully mechanized coal
cutting, simplifying the multi-cutting of the thick coal seams
into one-time cutting. The major breakthrough in the coal cutting
technique helped save two-thirds of the equipment and great amount
of workforce.
</P>
<P>
These efforts helped bring in more than 150 million yuan in
direct returns annually. In addition, it has spent over 40 million
yuan annually improving equipment and its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The number of work faces in coal mines with large thick coal
seams was cut to one to two from four to five, and the number of
miners on the cutting teams was cut from 25,000 in 1990 to the
present 16,000. In 1996, its seven teams mined 2.28 million tons
of coal each, and the group's annual coal output rose to 18.645
million tons from 10.07 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Last year, sales of more than 10 non-coal undertakings topped
two billion yuan, accounting for a third of the company's total
sales.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the group raised more than 300 million
yuan for these undertakings and started 30 new construction and
expansion projects, each costing over five million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the group had 1.2 billion yuan in pre-tax profits, and
664 million yuan in net profits. In the first five months of this
year, total sales were 1.9 billion yuan, with 250 million yuan
profits, up 35 percent and 62 percent respectively year-on-year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Cooperation in China's Yellow River Valley Beneficial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nine provinces and autonomous regions
along the Yellow River Valley in China have seen their combined
GDP, which was 1.485 trillion yuan by the end of last year,
increase 153.7 percent since 1988, the year they decided to get
involved in cross-border co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The rate of growth is 24.6 percentage points higher than the
national average, according to a report by the State Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
The valley has half of China's land mass and about two-fifths
of the country's 1.2 billion people, and runs all the way from
Qinghai Province in the far northwest to coastal Shandong Province
at the eastern end.
</P>
<P>
The inter-provincial co-operation has included improving
information exchanges, human resource training, sharing natural
resources, and industrial restructuring.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, there were 27,000 regional cooperation
projects involving more than 24 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Many companies in the eastern part of the river valley, where
the economy is more developed, are moving production to the west
to take advantage of the natural resources and cheap labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Summit Opens in Madrid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) today started its two-day summit, which was
described by its General Javier Solana as a "defining moment" for
a new NATO here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the summit, Solana said,
"We will open the doors of this alliance to the first new members
from Central and Eastern Europe."
</P>
<P>
"We will create new opportunities for co-operation and
partnership that will enhance the security of all nations in the
Euro-Atlantic area. And we will pursue our efforts to make NATO's
structures ready to face the challenges of the 21st century,"
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new NATO would be as indispensable to the
Europe of tomorrow as it was to the Europe of yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government of the NATO member states,
representatives of the Western European Union and the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe are present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, they will be joined by representatives from 27
members of NATO's Partnership for Peace (PfP) program. They are
Albania, Armenia, Austria, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bulgaria, the
Czech Republic, Estonia, Finland, Georgia, Hungary, Kazakhstan,
Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovakia,
Slovenia, Sweden, Switzerland, Macedonia, Turkmenistan, Ukraine,
and Uzbekistan. Malta ceased to be PfP member last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
