<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Gets Funds for Power project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved of
Kenya's request for 125-million-U.S.-Dollar credit for its power
development project scheduled to start soon, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the project, which has been dormant for more than
five years due to lack of funding, is attracting considerable
interest both from foreign donors and private financiers, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Co-financiers who have shown great interest include the
European Investment Banks, Kreditanstalt Fur Wie Deraufban (KFW)
of Germany and Oversea Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's offer, which is part of the 700 million
Dollors required for Kenya's energy reforms and power development#,
comes at a time when the Kenya Power and Lighting Company has
ended power rationing nationwide.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the project, spearheaded by the World
Bank, will definitely curb the power blackouts in the eastern
African country.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's total demand for industrial and commercial energy has
been rising steadily from 2.6 million tons of oil equivalent in
1991 to over 3.0 million tons in 1995, representing a growth rate
of 3.7 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
Kenya imported 72 percent of its total commercial energy,
comprising crude petroleum, coal and coke and hydro-electric
energy imported from Uganda, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has planned five major power projects
with a combined capacity of 338 megawatts to be added between
1997 and 2001 but the investment in the power sector of Kenya has
stalled after the suspension of donor aid in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
