<HEADLINE> Egyptian Cabinet Reshuffle Expected: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian newspapers indicated today
that a cabinet reshuffle is expected in hours or in days, with six
or seven ministers possibly being replaced.
</P>
<P>
The English newspaper The Egyptian Gazette reported that most
of the outgoing of the 30 ministers or state ministers are those
in charge of public services and economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet members with the key portfolios -- Defense Minister
Mohammed Hussein Tantawi, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Interior
Minister Hassan el-Alfy -- will probably remain in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Two portfolios are to be created, one for public works and the
other for Toshka, a major land-reclamation and development project
in southern and western Egypt, the Arabic newspaper Al Ahram
reported.
</P>
<P>
In remarks carried by the Al-Gomhuria newspaper Saturday,
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said that candidates would be
chosen carefully to ensure a smooth succession.
</P>
<P>
"It's not possible that I appoint a minister and then discover
after a couple of months that he is not suitable. Stability is the
key," Mubarak was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak met with Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri Monday as
expectations for an imminent cabinet shakeup soared. Later in the
day, Ganzouri again met with a couple of his ministers.
</P>
<P>
In a move seen related to the reshuffle, Youssef Boutros Ghali,
state minister for cabinet affairs, cut short his week-long visit
to London and was summoned home.
</P>
<P>
Rumors about injecting new blood to the one-year-old cabinet
have been rife since the beginning of this year. No new members
have joined the cabinet since Ganzouri took office in January 1996
and a vacancy caused by the death of a minister has yet to be
filled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
