<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Adopts New Vehicle Volume Reduction Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine capital of Manila
will start next Monday the implementation of a new modified
odd-even scheme for private vehicles in an attempt to ease the
city's traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
The new vehicle volume reduction program was announced here
today by Florencio Fianza, the new traffic executive director of
the Metro Manila Development Authority (MMDA).
</P>
<P>
Only private vehicles will be affected by the scheme, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new scheme, he said, all private vehicles will be off
the road of Metro Manila on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays if
their plate numbers end in 1, 3, 5, 7 and 9.
</P>
<P>
Those whose plate numbers end in 2, 4, 6, 8 and 0 will not be
authorized to use all Metro Manila's streets on Tuesdays,
Thursdays, and Saturdays, Fianza said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will be free-zone for private vehicles on
Sundays and holidays.
</P>
<P>
Violation of the new modified odd-even scheme will be penalized
as mandated in the previous program, Fianza said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Manila municipal authorities has tried several
schemes to ease traffic in the capital, including the odd-even
scheme.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city adopted a "Unified Vehicular Reduction
Program," under which, private cars whose plate numbers end in 0
or 1 are banned on the city's roads on Monday, 2 or 3 on Tuesday,
4 or 5 on Wednesday... The ban is lifted on Saturday and Sundays.
</P>
<P>
But all these programs have achieved little success. In Manila,
with 1.6 million vehicles on the roads, the travel speed of cars
is often limited to less than 20 kilometers during the rush hour.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, July 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said here
Tuesday the Madrid Summit would pave the way for a new NATO.
</P>
<P>
At the opening session of the summit, Solana said that NATO
would open its door to the first new members from Central and
Eastern Europe and create new opportunities for cooperation and
partnership, which "will enhance the security of all nations in
the Euro-Atlantic region."
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's economy will grow 6.3 percent in the
second half of this year, up 0.7 percentage point from the first
half of the year, the Bank of Korea (BOK) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- The deadlock in Bangladesh's largest seaport
Chittagong continued for the sixth day today as several rounds of
multilateral negotiations failed to settle the hassle between the
two rival unions. Port sources said a seven-hour meeting among
port authorities, leaders of the striking workers and hatch
workers ended late Monday night without any tangible results.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- President of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) Laurent Kabila on Monday accused some members of the
international community of conducting a smear campaign against his
government.
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The city is quiet here this morning after the
authorities lifted an 8 pm to 6 pm curfew on Monday
afternoon. Australian Prime Minister John Howard said Australia
would closely monitor developments in Cambodia and was prepared to
evacuate Australians if the situation in the troubled Southeast
Asian nation worsened.
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Albanian President and Democratic Party Chairman Sali
Berisha said on Monday that his party would exist as a
constructive opposition party in the country. 
</P>
