<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Delivery System Declines in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's health delivery system
has deteriorated considerably, with doctors and nurses leaving
government services in great numbers,the daily ''the Herald''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was mainly caused by a 40 percent decline in per capita
expenditure on health since the launch of economic reforms in
1991, the report said.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 nurses, including the 300 who were dismissed
following a nationwide strike last year, and some 14 doctors,
have resigned from government employment over the past 12 months
alone.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health and Child Welfare has 1,500 vacant
posts for nurses, and about 80 other vacancies for doctors, said
Paulinus Sikhosana, secretary for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Although the government had increased the training capacity of
nurses, the move was not helping as such, since the Ministry of
Health was only able to retain between 50 and 60 percent of the
trained nurses.
</P>
<P>
To boost its manpower, the government was now offering nurses
training posts at all its provincial hospitals countrywide.
</P>
</TEXT>
