<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Diversion Project In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A groundbreaking ceremony was held
today for a water diversion project in Baiyin City, northwest
China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The project will divert water from the Datong River, which
originates on the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau, to arid
poverty-stricken areas of Gaolan and Baiyin, in Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction work for the 40.0-long project will include 57
tunnels and a reservoir with a storage capacity of 10 million
cu.m. The project will help provide irrigation for more than 4,400
ha of land.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the project, which will cost 100 million yuan,
will help eliminate poverty for 40,000 local people after it is
competed at the end of next year. It will also provide cleaner
and healthier water for more than 300,000 residents in the city of
Baiyin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
