<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Price Crash Forces S. African Mine Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The plummeting gold price in
global market has forced a South African gold mine to close,
local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Benoni Gold, a wholly owned subsidiary of Boksburg-based East
Rand Proprietary Mines, announced yesterday it had decided to
close due to technical hitchers and a free-falling gold price,
which had erased its monthly profit of 500,000 Rand (111,111 U.S.
dollars ).
</P>
<P>
Gold price slumped to a 10-and-a half year low of 315 U.S.
dollars an ounce at the close in London from last Friday's 324.50
dollars. In New York it lost seven dollars from last Thursday's
finish to close 318.25 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Johannesburg Stock Exchange's all gold index yesterday
followed gold's fall, hitting its lowest level in four-and-a-half
years.
</P>
<P>
The South African currency of Rand also weakened, losing
almost a cent to 4.5370 Rand a dollar, while bonds followed suit,
local finanncial sources said.
</P>
<P>
Following the gold crash in the world market, about 60 percent
of world gold production was being mined at a loss, analysts
said, predicting that only five gold mines in South Africa could
produce gold profitably if the price fell below 300 dollars an
ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
