<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 08:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel OK's Global Accord on Information Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government has
ratified the World Trade Ministerial Declaration on trade and
information technology products to liberalize further its market,
reported The Jerusalem Post newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Trade and Industry announced Monday that
Israel will accordingly cut customs duties on computer and
telecommunications products immediately, and gradually eliminate
them by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The 40 participants in the accord include the U.S. and European
Union members, with whom Israel already has free-trade agreements,
and Japan, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, South Korea,
Australia and Thailand, which are non-free-trade partners.
</P>
<P>
The agreement gives Israel an opportunity to join the markets
"we've never been able to get into," said Marcia Harpaz, director
of the ministry's multinational affairs department.
</P>
<P>
The document also stipulates that import taxes on more
sensitive products, such as telephone switches, antennas, printed
circuits and certain cables must be eliminated by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The information technology accord is the second of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) agreements designed to liberalize world
markets.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the year, the WTO issued a global accord to free the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which went into effect in February, paved the
way for Israel's two private telephone companies, Barak and Golden
Lines, to enter the markets usually controlled by state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The WTO is now negotiating a financial services accord that
would liberalize the banking, insurance and foreign exchange
rates regulations. Such an accord would be designed to make the
international investment environment more secure.
</P>
<P>
Israel produces close to 1 percent of the world's information
technology products. Information technology is a 500 billion
U.S. dollars market worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port Deadlock Continues Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The deadlock in Bangladesh's largest
seaport Chittagong continued for the sixth day today as several
rounds of multilateral negotiations failed to settle the hassle
between the two rival unions.
</P>
<P>
Port sources said a seven-hour meeting among port authorities,
leaders of the striking workers and hatch workers ended late
Monday night without any tangible results.
</P>
<P>
The merchant workers started the strike Thursday afternoon in
protest against engagement of hatch workers in lighterage of cargo
from ships anchored at the outer anchorage.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, who just ended her six-day visit
to Japan on Sunday, has pledged that her government would take
initiatives to break the stalemate immediately.
</P>
<P>
She said that this untoward situation had been created at a
time when the government was trying its best to lure foreign
investment. An incident like this in the country's principal port
would give foreign investors a wrong impression about the
situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eleven opposition lawmakers in a joint statement on
Monday demanded a judicial inquiry into the deadlock at Chittagong
port.
</P>
<P>
These lawmakers blamed the ruling party's local leaders and
several officials of the port for the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Up till today, over 30 ships including nine ships at the outer
anchorage got stranded while each stranded ship had been incurring
an average demurrage of 10,000 U.S. dollars a day, which
ultimately would be passed on to the importers.
</P>
<P>
According to Customs officials, the amount of revenue loss
which has been incurred in the strike stood over one billion taka
(about 23 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that the rivalry between the two union -- the
Merchant Workers' Union and the Coaster Hatch Workers Union -- has
been continuing for a long time over the sharing of work at the
hatch of vessels at the outer sea.
</P>
<P>
The hatch workers said that they were driven out from their
work by the merchant workers by force in 1986 and they were
struggling for the last few years to get back their right of
handling lighterage works at the outer sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
