<HEADLINE> Traffic Accidents Down in Uganda's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Traffic accidents in the Ugandan
capital Kampala have reduced by 40 percent in the first six
months this year due to police vigilance, the local daily "the
New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the police authority said the total
number of accidents in the first six months of 1997 was recorded
at 1991, a remarkable drop from the 3,335 in the same period of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of vehicles involved in the accidents also reduced
from 4,898 to 2,891, representing a 41 percent decrease, said the
press release.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved this through rigorous intensified checks on
all routes and roads leading into and out of the city," the
release said, adding that it is still unfortunate that 125
persons were killed for the past six months.
</P>
<P>
Most drivers have been subjected to a retest especially those
whose driving licences were in doubt, said the press release,
adding measures like this have forced city drivers with fake
licences to abandon driving completely.
</P>
<P>
To reduce accidents further, the police will continue to
promote road safety awareness to the road users through seminars,
the media and school education programs, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
