<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Central Bank Optimistic on National Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's economy will grow 6.3
percent in the second half of this year, up 0.7 percentage point
from the first half of the year, the Bank of Korea (BOK) said
today.
</P>
<P>
For the whole year, the average growth rate will be 6 percent,
the central bank predicted.
</P>
<P>
Although corporate investment in equipment and plants will
continue to be sluggish, exports, construction investment and
private consumption will be on the upswing, boosting the economy
in the period, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the current account deficit for the entire year
will be 17 billion U.S. dollars, one billion dollars less than
its March projection.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices will rise 4.3 percent in 1997, down 0.2
percentage point from last year's 4.5 percent. The inflation rate
will be 2.4 percent and 1.9 percent for the first and second half
of the year respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bright economic prospects for the second half are not based on
the government's industrial restructuring policy aimed at
increasing the international competitiveness of South Korean
products through cost-effective management, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the increase to better external economic
conditions, such as increasing world trade and the strong Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
But they also said that financial shortage will continue to
trouble many businesses, discouraging them from ambitious
investment in new equipment and machinery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
