<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets With President of Bolivian Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Rong Yiren,
meeting in Beijing this morning with Raul Lema Patino, President
of the Senate of the National Congress of Bolivia, said he hopes
that Sino-Bolivian economic and trade cooperation can be further
promoted.
</P>
<P>
Rong said that Bolivia's President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada's
successful state visit to China in March made a new contribution
to the development of bilateral co-operation for mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes Lema's visit will further the development
of bilateral friendship and cooperation, and noted that although
China and Bolivia are far from each other, bilateral relations
have developed smoothly since the two countries forged diplomatic
ties.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the two countries have continuously
strengthened co-operation in politics, the economy, trade and
culture, and that the co-operation has been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
China is pleased to see that in the past few years, under the
leadership of President Sanchez, the Bolivian government has made
an effort to promote political stability and economic prosperity,
and to improve the Bolivian people's lives, and has had some
remarkable achievements, Rong said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China and Bolivia are both developing
countries facing the common task of safeguarding national
sovereignty and developing the national economy, and that the two
countries, as trusted friends, share similar views on many issues
and have supported each other and had close co-operation in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Lema congratulated China on the return of Hong Kong, and said
that the return shows again that Chinese people have a high-degree
of wisdom and patience. He noted that since China adopted its
reforms and opening-up policy, it has accomplished a lot in
economic construction and in improving people's lives.
</P>
<P>
Lema said he hopes to further strengthen bilateral political,
economic and cultural co-operation, as well as co-operation among
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Lema reiterated that Bolivia will stick to the "One China"
policy.
</P>
<P>
