<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Exchange Oil for Philippines' Food Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq will exchange its oil products
for the Philippines' food and other commodities under a 185
million U.S. dollar trade accord signed between the two countries,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the trade agreement was signed by the two
countries when an Iraqi mission visited Manila recently.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had proposed an oil-for-food counter-trade scheme under
which it will exchange its oil for Philippine food products, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil trade is regulated under United Nations trade
sanctions imposed on the country as a consequence of its 1991
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
But the United Nations allows Iraq to spend up to four billion
dollars from its oil revenue for basic commodity imports including
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the trade accord, Manila will export to
Baghdad cooking oil, palm oil, sugar, rice, milk and detergents
and medicine, the agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
