<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Introduce High-tech Mobile Post Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli Postal Authority
(IPA) is to introduce 10 high-tech mobile post offices by the end
of this year to provide convenient on-line banking and
telecommunications services, according to local press today.
</P>
<P>
The new facilities, said to be the world's first computerized
mobile post offices, are linked by a cellular phone line to the
Postal Bank computer. The first such a mobile unit has been very
successful in its trial run.
</P>
<P>
The IPA has shown the new facility to the members of the
Knesset (Israeli parliament) Economics Committee during their
recent visit to the authority in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Moshe Tery, director-general of the authority, said that by
the end of this year, another 10 computerized mobile offices
would be shuttling around the country to provide services to
local communities. There are urrently 50 mobile post routes.
</P>
<P>
The cellular-linked mobile post offices will provide on-line
banking and telecommunication services to 1,000 small communities
in the periphery, Tery said.
</P>
<P>
By using the mobile services, customers will be able to
transfer vehicle ownership, receive National Insurance Institute
payments, exchange foreign currencies, remit money overseas and
buy compulsory vehicle insurance from insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
Postal Bank Director Moshe Tepper said the linkage to its
central IBM computer would allow customers to carry out
transactions in real time rather than order such services in
advance.
</P>
<P>
The mobile post office was designed by a team from Masad, or
the country's Computerized Postal Branches, with the help from
IPA staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
