<HEADLINE> Kabila Criticises Smear Campaign Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 8 (Xinhua) -- President of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) Laurent Kabila on Monday accused some
members of the international community of conducting a smear
campaign against his government.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, arrived in Namibia on Monday for a two-day state visit
at the invitation of Namibian President Sam Nujoma, made the
remarks at a banquet in his honour at State House in Windhoek,
capital of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said there was a lot of evidence that the smear
campaign was by the same great power that "does not wish well to
the Democratic Republic of Congo", formerly known as Zaire, local
press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the refugee problem, Kabila said that not even
France or the United Nations High Commission for Refugees had
been able to achieve what he had done -- send home one million
Hutu refugees to neighbouring Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"Not one of the great power said thand you," he said.
</P>
<P>
The international community, some members of which "shared the
cake" in the former Zaire until former president Mobutu Sese Seko
was ousted in May, did not demand democracy for more than 30
years, but it was demanded of his new government in just three
days, Kabila said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day tour to Namibia is Kabila's second official visit
out of his new DRC since taking power in May.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Kabila and Nujoma held official discussions about
the possibility of Namibia drawing water from the Congo River,
the bilateral cooperation in the fields of transport,
communications and economic relationship between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
