<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Publicizing The Hong Kong Basic Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Wu Jianfan became famous over night
earlier this year when he was asked to talk to President Jiang
Zemin and other Chinese leaders about the ABCs of the Basic Law of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, at Zhongnanhai,
headquarters of the Chinese Communist Party and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
And, he became busier than ever. "After that, I had to deal
with several calls from different people and units every day, all
inviting me to give the same lecture to them," said the
mild-mannered member of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Wu was a member of a panel that drafted the law that supports
the "One Country, Two Systems" and encourages Hong Kong people to
rule Hong Kong. "Jiang Zemin and other Chinese leaders, listened
carefully, took notes seriously, and raised a number of profound
questions," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Wu's lecture was broadcast by China Central Television to
millions of viewers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The law took effect on July 1, when Hong Kong returned to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"It is wrong to think that the Basic Law is implemented in Hong
Kong and has nothing to do with the inland areas. It is the
concern of the whole nation and relates to every citizen," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
The law was approved by the National People's Congress, China's
top legislature, in April of 1990. Since then, Chinese lawmakers
and government workers have been publicizing it.
</P>
<P>
Anything related to the Basic Law over the past seven years was
covered by the media in detail.
</P>
<P>
First, it is a stunning historical event rather than an
abstract text and included the Sino-British negotiations, the
election of the administrative executive, and the establishment of
the provisional legislature. These showed many Chinese people how
important the law is, Wu explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Publicizing Hong Kong Basic Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the past few years, dozens of different versions of the
Basic Law have appeared on the market, ranging from books and
picture albums to audio and visual aids. Some experts say that
more than 10 million copies of the full text have been distributed
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Xin Guangwei, a member of the Press and Publications
Administration, said that the publicity campaign is unusual in
terms of scale when compared with similar programs for other laws.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the handover, "People's Daily", Xinhua and other
key state news sources were busy releasing editorials and
commentaries on the importance of the law. The barrage was
supported by other powerful media. Internet even had a web site
operated by the telecommunications department.
</P>
<P>
Officers and enlisted men of the Chinese People's Liberation
Army (PLA) to be stationed in Hong Kong also became students of
the law. "Studying it enabled us to better understand the defense
system in Hong Kong as well as our responsibilities," noted Xiong
Ziren, political commissar of the troops.
</P>
<P>
The PLA's General Political Department then ordered the army as
a whole to study the law.
</P>
<P>
The law has understandably caught the attention of business
people. "Executives from Chinese enterprises in Hong Kong say that
they will firmly observe the law," said Gu Yongjiang, who is in
charge of a Chinese business association in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The general public also showed a great deal of interest. One
contest that was held by Guangzhou's Yangcheng Evening News
attracted 100,000 readers who wrote in answers to questions
like: "What does the HKSAR emblem looks like?"
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese capital, some 1,000 lawyers took to the streets
and lanes to explain the law to local citizens. And one agency
even sent its employees to villages to explain to farmers just
what "One Country, Two Systems" means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0226 </DOCNO>
