<HEADLINE> Phom Penh's Situation Calms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The city is quiet here this
morning after the authorities lifted an 8 pm to 6 pm curfew on
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard said Australia would
closely monitor developments in Cambodia and was prepared to
evacuate Australians if the situation in the troubled Southeast
Asian nation worsened.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand prepared to fly military aircraft into the
city to take its citizens home, while the streets here were tense
and largely deserted after a day of chaotic scenes and looting.
</P>
<P>
A Thai embassy official in Phnom Penh said Thai military
transport planes would arrive in Phnom Penh today to offer flights
to Thais who would like to go home.
</P>
<P>
Phnom Penh airport has been closed since early Saturday when
fighting between troops loyal to one or the other of the country's
two prime ministers erupted in the city, reportedly killing more
than 10 people.
</P>
<P>
But the airport was stripped of all equipment and ransacked
during looting on Monday, a senior aviation official said.
</P>
<P>
Tourists and aid workers in the northern town of Siem Reap were
reported to be preparing to drive in convoy to Thailand on
Tuesday. 
</P>
