<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM, Former PM Clash Over Genocide Tag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard has clashed with former Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser over
the latter's claim that forced removals of aboriginal children
from their parents amounted to genocide.
</P>
<P>
The former prime minister has backed a Human Rights and Equal
Opportunity Commission (HREOC) report which finds that the
practice of forced removals of up to 100,000 aboriginal children
from their families during 1910 and 1970 was genocide under
international law definition.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard said today the word genocide was
inappropriate term for practices of assimilation.
</P>
<P>
"I stand by the statements I have made previously that to use
the word genocide in relation to the practices of the removal of
children was inappropriate," Howard told a local radio.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said yesterday that the term genocide was appropriate
because the policy has sought to achieve the disappearance of the
aboriginal race over a long term. He warned that Australia faced a
moral crisis over its handling of aboriginal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Howard said: "I know all Australians, myself included, would
regard them (the practices of forced removals) in this day and age
as utterly and completely unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
"To use the word genocide was the wrong use of the word and I
understand that we will have to agree to disagree," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has said its legal advice is that the
practices do not fulfill the requirements for the definition of
genocide under international laws.
</P>
<P>
Fraser said today he was unaware his statement contradicted
views put by the government.
</P>
<P>
Howard offered personal apology late last May to aboriginal
people over the sufferings inflicted upon them by the official
practices of the removals.
</P>
<P>
The HREOC report issued last May calls for government apology
for the practices and financial compensation for the victims. The
proposal was rejected by government ministers.
</P>
<P>
Justice Marcus Einfeld, who was former head of the official
Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission, said yesterday
Australian political leaders should recognize the "violent
history" of black-white relations in the same way former South
African President F W de Klerk apologized for apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Einfeld said he felt ashamed of the government policy of
destroying aboriginal culture by forcibly removing children from
their families and culture.
</P>
<P>
Some state governor and church leaders have apologized formally
for the practices of removal during the past month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
