<HEADLINE> Illness Costs Canada Billions A Year: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada paid a total of 113 billion
U.S. dollars for the sick and injured and premature deaths in
1993, a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Health Canada said in a report that direct costs such as
hospitals, doctors' bills, drugs and research amounted to 53
billion U.S. dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Hospital costs were the highest single item at 18.7 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Indirect costs, such as lost productivity, reached 61 billion
U.S. dollars. Long-term disability was the highest single
indirect costs, totaling 27.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said that cardiovascular illness was the single most
costly item, accounting for 14.2 billion U.S. dollars. Muscle and
skeletal disease was second at 12.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Injuries was ranked third at 10.3 billion dollars and cancer
was fourth on the list with costs of 9.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
