<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nomura Suspected of Having Paid Two More Racketeers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan's biggest brokerage, Nomura
Securities, is suspected of having paid a total of 110 million yen
(980,000 U.S. dollars) in cash to a further two "sokaiya,"
corporate racketeers, as compensation for stock investment losses
before 1993, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The cash was used to make up for losses stemming from stock
deals made by Nomura dealers for the accounts of the two sokaiya,
a practice that runs counter to Japan's Securities and Exchange
Law, sources familiar with the case were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The payment in question also violates the Commercial Code,
which bans corporate payoffs to sokaiya. However, the two sokaiya
cannot be charged because the three-year statute of limitations
has run out.
</P>
<P>
Nomura is embroiled in a scandal involving alleged payments to
sokaiya Ryuichi Koike who has been indicted on charges of
receiving 49.7 million yen (440,000 dollars) from Nomura between
January and June 1995 for agreeing not to disrupt a Nomura
shareholders meeting in June that year.
</P>
<P>
He is also suspected of taking 320 million yen (2.83 million
dollars) in cash from Nomura to cover stock investment losses in
March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The scandal, the second involving Nomura in six years, has led
to the arrest of four Nomura executives, including its former
President Hideo Sakamaki. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
