<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Slashes Tariffs, Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has cut
import tariffs on 1,600 items, slashed the number of local taxes
and fees, banned new loans for land acquisition and development,
and allowed imports of used cargo and fishing vessels.
</P>
<P>
These measures were stipulated in a new package of economic
reforms announced last night.
</P>
<P>
"The measures are a continuation of preceding deregulation
policies aimed at improving efficiency and simultaneously to
confirm our commitment to multilateral trade agreements,"
Coordinating Minister for Economy and Finance Saleh Afiff said.
</P>
<P>
The package cuts tariff rates on 1,461 industrial products, 136
agricultural commodities and three health products.
</P>
<P>
"After this latest deregulation package, 62.55 percent of the
total tariff codes will be in the range of 0 to 10 percent," said
Afiff.
</P>
<P>
Afiff said the number of items with zero tariff rose to 1,419
from 1,399, while the number of items with a 5 percent tariff rose
to 2,275 from 2,066. Those with a 10 percent tariff increased to
1,556 from 610.
</P>
<P>
"This reform decreased Indonesian average, unweighted import
tariffs from 13 percent to 11.9 percent, the second lowest in
Southeast Asian countries after Singapore," he said.
</P>
<P>
No further details on the tariff reductions were immediately
available as the government only announced a summary of the
ministerial decrees, rules and directives which enforce the
measures.
</P>
<P>
A complete set of the measures in technical detail is to be
distributed today.
</P>
<P>
The government last year introduced two reform packages in
January and June respectively.
</P>
<P>
The measures also free imports of used fishing and cargo
vessels in a bid to further develop efficient inter-island
freighter services and bolster the fisheries industry.
</P>
<P>
In an another concerted drive to reduce the costs of doing
business in the country, the number of local taxes was cut from 42
to nine and local fees or levies from 192 categories to 30
categories.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in an effort to control increased lending to the
property sector, Bank Indonesia issued a decree Monday which bans
new loans for land acquisition and development by property
companies, except for the development of cheap housing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
