<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12 Killed in Renewed Clash in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 Muslim rebels were
killed and seven army soldiers wounded Monday when the two sides
clashed fiercely anew in central Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted again when the separatist Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) guerrillas shelled a former MILF camp they
lost to the military late last month, the reports quoted a
military spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Capt. Noel Detoyato, spokesman for the Army's Sixth Infantry
Division, said the government troops, backed by tanks and
helicopter gunships, had repulsed the attack by the rebels on Camp
Rajah Muda in Pikit town, Cotabato province.
</P>
<P>
The government troops overran the camp, the second largest MILF
headquarters, on June 28 after two weeks of military offensives.
The MILF had vowed to retake the camp and had been massing its
forces in preparation for a siege.
</P>
<P>
The latest outbreak of hostilities in the region has dimmed
prospects of reopening exploratory talks between the government
and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which suspended peace talks with Manila soon after
the fall of Rajah Muda, Monday laid down four conditions for the
group to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The conditions include cessation of military operations by the
government and return of all government troops to the barracks in
the region. But these conditions were reportedly rejected by the
military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
