<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major economic
news briefs from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur), a regional
economic bloc grouping Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay and
Chile:
</P>
<P>
-- The first Mercosur summit on mining will be held this
November to analyze a number of common problems and progress made
in the sector by each of the member countries.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that for this occasion, the systematization of
mining legislations of the member countries of this bloc to adopt
a joint integral standard for this sector will have been
completed, said Gonzalo Olarramendi, the mining and geology
director for Uruguay's Ministry of Industry, Energy and Mining.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil will increase its purchases of natural
gas from Bolivia between 1998-1999 by 133 percent, announced
Petrobras, Brazil's state-owned oil company.
</P>
<P>
Bolivian gas imports will climb from 9 million cubic meters in
December 1998 to 21 million cubic meters in the last year of this
century, said a Petrobras report released last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's trade deficit during the first half of
this year reached 4.71 billion U.S. dollars, or 85 percent of last
year's total deficit.
</P>
<P>
This deficit is the result of 24.787 billion U.S. dollars worth
of exports and 29.502 billion U.S. dollars worth of imports.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts expect a total deficit of 11 billion U.S.
dollars for the whole of this year.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- In September, Uruguay will initiate its exports
of Renault pick-up trucks to Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The Renault "Express" which is a pick-up truck capable of
transporting 700 kilograms of cargo has been leading sales in the
European market during the past 5 years.
</P>
<P>
It expects to export 24,000 units in the next 3 years: 15,000
to Argentina and 9,000 to Brazil for a total of 208 million U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
