<HEADLINE> PRI Leading in Mexican Congressional Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) is leading the number of votes cast in
Sunday's elections to elect deputies and senators for Mexico's
congress, the local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the ballot counting completed for 85 percent of
the vote-counting tables, the PRI is leading with 38.69 percent of
the 25,435,391 votes cast while the National Action Party or PAN
has received 27.08 and the Democratic Revolution Party (PRD) has
25.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
In elections simultaneously held for Federal District mayor,
opposition PRD candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas has consolidated his
lead to become the virtual winner by receiving 3,190,815 votes.
</P>
<P>
So far, Cardenas has accumulated 47 percent of the votes
counted, versus 25.56 percent by PRI candidate Alfredo Del Mazo to
govern over Mexico City. 
