<HEADLINE> Brazil Footwear Production Expected to Rise Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The shoe-making industry in
Brazil will have a 10 percent increase in production this year
over 1996, says the Brazilian Association of Footwear Industries.
</P>
<P>
Association president Invanio Batista was quoted by the local
press as saying today that the growth was due to monetary
stabilization, higher productivity and more investments in
technology.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Brazilian shoe makers produced 585 million pairs of
footwear and had gross billings of 600 million U.S. dollars. Of
these, 143 million pairs, or 24.4 percent, were exported to other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the second largest producer of footwear in the world,
after China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
