<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Forest Products Seized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities seized
nearly 198 tons of illegal forest products in the country's Bago
division at the end of last month, the official paper The New
Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The forest products, which were confiscated mostly in the
Nyaunglebin township by local Forest Department Authorities,
include Pyingado (hardwood), charcoal, turpentine, pine wood and
canes.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's hardwood export in the 1996-97 fiscal year ended
March was estimated at 142,000 cubic meters, while that of teak at
184,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The export of Myanmar's forest products amounted to 218 million
U.S. dollars in the 1996-97 fiscal year, accounting for 24.4
percent of the total export, second only to that of agricultural
products, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs, banning the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood products
is encouraged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
