<HEADLINE> UN to Help China Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations' Development
Program (UNDP) will give 1.89 million US dollars to the Chinese
Government to fight HIV/AIDS in the next four years, today's China
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on co-operation has been drawn up and will be
signed soon between UNDP and several Chinese ministries and
provincial governments, according to the UNDP's China Office.
</P>
<P>
The four-year project, which starts this month, aims to assist
the central government and the provincial governments of Fujian,
Guangdong and Hainan in preventing and controlling HIV
transmission.
</P>
<P>
To be developed are appropriate responses directed to
communities and population groups with the highest risks of
acquiring HIV. These activities will be supported by
multi-sectional efforts at national and local levels and
complemented by national policy development, said the UNDP official.
</P>
<P>
The project will help increase the management and training
capacity of the Ministry of Health, increase HIV/STD programs in
other ministries and carry out intervention activities among
high-risk population groups, said Shen Jie, division chief in
charge of HIV/AIDS and sexually transmitted diseases control with
the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Shen said she was very satisfied with previous UNDP-China
collaborations in this field. UNDP started to aid China in
HIV/AIDS control in the summer of 1993.
</P>
<P>
The country received 1.1 million US dollars from UNDP during
the last three and half years to carry out activities aimed at
minimizing HIV transmission.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP also helped the country establish the capacity to
produce high quality educational written, audio and visual
materials that can be reproduced and distributed in the country.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Help Laid-off Workers Find New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 8 (Xinhua) -- China has asked local officials to
try harder to find employment for laid-off workers and guarantee
their basic living standard this year, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labour, along with another 11 government
departments, has jointly issued a directive ordering provincial
officials to create new jobs for more than half of local jobless
workers.
</P>
<P>
The rules apply to China's pilot cities chosen for implementing
bankruptcies: Under State guidance, these cities urge debt-laden
State enterprises to declare bankruptcy. While ending loss-making
operations, this restructuring does exact a toll.
</P>
<P>
The government has expanded the number of these key pilot
cities to 111 this year from 58.
</P>
<P>
The four million jobless and laid-off workers will gain new
employment opportunities through a re-employment project, said
Labour Minister Li Boyong.
</P>
<P>
Labour departments should play an active role in helping make
macro-economic policy, promoting job opportunities and helping
labourers adjust to the market economy including training schemes,
Li said.
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, the number of urban and rural labourers
will increase greatly. Li estimated there are 13.7 million urban
people to be settled while only 7.8 million people can find
jobs. Unemployment will hit 5.9 million by the end of this year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
To ease the pressure on laid-off workers from State
enterprises, the re-employment project will continue to be
launched, while at the same time deepening economic reform in the
200 selected pilot cities, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials should also take measures to prevent workers'
income from falling short of the minimum living standard set by
each municipal government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
