<HEADLINE> Greece Pledges to Support Socialists in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government pledged today
to support Albania's Socialist Party after the latter won a
landslide victory in the country's general elections on June 29.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a telephone conversation, Greece's Prime Minister
Costas Simitis told Albania's Socialist Party leader Fatos Nano
that Athens would be "on the side of Albania" and offered to
provide assistance to restore order in the neighboring country,
acting government spokesman Nikos Athanasakis told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Athanasakis said that Nano officially informed Simitis that his
party had won a two-thirds majority in the Albanian parliament
over President Sali Berisha's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that the Greek troops participating in
the Italian-led multinational protection force in Albania would
begin its gradual withdrawal from the country on 18 July.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the Greek contingent could prolong their
presence in Albania if the new Albanian government hoped them to
do so.
</P>
<P>
The general elections in Albania came after months of civil
conflict sparked by the collapse of pyramid investment schemes in
January. More than 1,500 people were killed in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Greece said recently that it hoped the completion of the
electoral process in Albania would result in a government of the
widest possible consensus to undertake the work of restoring order
in the country. 
