<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer Equalls 800m World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Wilson Kipketer of Denmark was on
a edge to break the oldest world track record on Monday when he
equalled Sebastian Coe's 16-year-old 800 meters mark at the
Stockholm Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan-born Dane was clocked one minute 41,73 seconds to
have a share of the world record. However, the clock first showed
that Kipketer was timed at one minute 41.74 seconds, 0.01 of a
second outside Coe's mark.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer emigrated to Denmark in 1990, was ranked world number
one in 1994 and raced away with the world title in Gothenburg in
the following year.
</P>
<P>
Following protests by the Kenyan Federation he was not allowed
to compete for Denmark at last year's Atlanta Olympics but was
still the world number one with five successive times under 1:42.
</P>
<P>
He broke the world indoor record twice at the Paris world
championships in March and was clearly set to mount a serious
assault on a mark which has defied the best two-lap runners in the
world since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Three times world steeplechase champion Moses Kiptanui, who had
not trained since the middle of last month through illness, failed
in a valiant bid on his own world record earlier in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
But his time of 8:01.80 was still the third fastest in history
and only the Kenyan himself has ever run faster.
</P>
<P>
Moroccan Hicham el Guerrouj, just half a second outside
Noureddine Morceli's world mile record in Oslo on Friday, was
again a disappointed man.
</P>
<P>
El Guerrouj clocked 3:29.30 seconds over 1,500, outside
Morceli's world mark. But it was the fastest time of the year and
only Morceli has ever run faster.
</P>
<P>
One man clearly delighted with his night's work on a sweltering
Scandinavian evening at the venue which staged the 1912 Olympics
was Trinidad's Ato Boldon.
</P>
<P>
Boldon, bronze medallist in both the 100 and 200 in Atlanta,
won the 100 in 9.95 seconds and followed with victory in the 200
in 19.82 seconds, fastest this year and sixth fastest of all time.
</P>
<P>
The impressive American 100 champion Marion Jones won the
women's 200 in a year's best of 22.16 and there was another year's
best for Slovenia's Igor Kovacs who clocked 13.13 with a following
wind of 1.6 meters in the 110 meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
Despite the string of world class performances in the
penultimate grand prix before the world championships, the most
popular man of the night was nine times Olympic champion Carl
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
Lewis, sporting a new hairstyle which gave him a passing
resemblance to former French tennis champion Yannick Noah,
anchored the Santa Monica Track Club to victory in the 4x100 relay
and was still signing autographs in the infield well after the
meeting had finished. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
