<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fire Declines Markedly in Southeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian Province
has seen a dramatic decrease in the number of forest fires this
year, thanks to local greater attention paid to forest fire
control.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of the year, there were 127 forest fires
in the province, a big drop from the figure 417 that hit during
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the amount of forests destroyed by fire fell to
1,278 ha. from 4,346 ha. in 1996, and the number of casualties was
down 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
As part of this effort, 25,000 km of fire-prevention belts were
built and professional forest fire brigades were organized in most
of the 38 major counties in the vast forest area.
</P>
<P>
The larger amount of spring rainfall this year also helped keep
down the threat of forest fires in the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
