<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Speeds up Construction of Key Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 23.5 billion yuan is to be
invested in 58 key projects in southwest China's Sichuan Province
this year, a 42 percent rise over the figure for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Most of the projects will involve infrastructure construction
and hi-tech industries, such as iron and steel plants, railways,
highways and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
The projects are expected to include the building of 14
satellite ground stations, and the adding of five million kw of
electricity generating capacity, more than two billion cu m of
reservoirs and nearly 240,000 ha of irrigated land. In addition,
more than 710 km of railways, 157 km of electrified railway lines
and 403 km of highways will be built.
</P>
<P>
In order to speed up such construction, the province has raised
money from different channels and has introduced nearly 1.7
billion yuan of overseas investment for 15 projects. Also, nearly
1.1 billion yuan has also been raised by enterprises and through
the issuing of stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
