<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Approves British Takeover of MCI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department
today approved the British Telecommunications (BT) takeover of MCI
Communications, a deal which is regarded as the biggest foreign
takeover of a U.S. corporation.
</P>
<P>
The department's green light clears a crucial regulatory hurdle
for the purchase of the nation's second-largest long-distance
company.
</P>
<P>
However, the proposed merger still requires approval from the
Federal Communications Commission (FCC) and a few state regulatory
bodies, including one in California.
</P>
<P>
The European Union in May okayed the proposed merger subject to
conditions to protect competition. The shareholders of the BT and
MCI also have approved the transaction.
</P>
<P>
When the London-based British Telecommunications and MCI
Communications announced their merger proposal in November of
1996, the deal was valued at 20.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Globally, the combined company would rank second only to AT&AMP;T
as a long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
The combined company would have annual revenues of 43 billion
dollars and 43 million business and residential customers in 72
countries. It would be called Concert, after a joint venture began
four years ago when the BT bought a 20 percent stake in MCI.
</P>
<P>
British Telecom shareholders would have about 66 percent of
Concert, and MCI shareholders the rest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, US Lobby for Tax-Free Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Both German and U.S. officials said
here today that governments should not levy new taxes on business
conducted over the Internet and, instead, they should turn it into
a "free trade zone."
</P>
<P>
Addressing an international meeting on Internet opened in Bonn
today, German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt said, "We must
support digital commerce and should not put it under new burdens."
</P>
<P>
Noting that trade over the Internet could reach several hundred
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000, Rexrodt said governments
should allow the international computer network to develop as free
as possible in order to make full use of its economic potential.
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt's U.S. counterpart, William Daley, today also warned
against too many national regulations on the Internet. "The
Internet should not become a national market," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton issued a report last week deciding
not to impose new taxes or regulations on business conducted over
the Internet and instead will largely allow the private sector to
determine on its own how it will operate in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
Daley said the United States and the European Union (EU) have
more common ground on this issue than their differences.
</P>
<P>
Despite the support for a market-oriented approach, EU
commissioner Martin Bangemann said at the meeting in Bonn that the
EU still favors a set of minimum international regulations to
safeguard the Internet against criminal content and to enable data
protection.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
meanwhile announced in Bonn that it would organize a conference in
Canada in autumn next year to discuss necessary Internet
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Internet meeting in Bonn was sponsored by the EU and were
attended by 40 government ministers and 80 international companies
and organizations. On Tuesday, the EU ministers are expected to
adopt a unbinding declaration to make clear their positions on the
use of the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
