<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 100 Countries to Observe World Population Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 countries will
commemorate World Population Day on July 11 with special events,
according to the UN Department of Public Information.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued today, the UN department reported
that the theme for this year's observance is adolescent
reproductive health care. In particular, the focus is on the need
to provide adolescents with sex education and reproductive health
care so that they can make informed choices, including how to
protect themselves from unwanted pregnancy and sexually
transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
Among the events planned throughout the world are rallies and
speeches by national and local leaders; lectures; seminars; radio,
television and film programs; newspaper and magazine supplements;
special publications; exhibits and sports events.
</P>
<P>
To mark World Population Day, the United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA) is issuing three booklets: "Generation 97," the
results of a survey of the views of young women and men on sexual
and reproductive health; "The Youth Perspective," which includes
the winning entries of the 1996 International Youth Essay Contest
of the UNFPA; and "UNFPA and Adolescents," a discussion of the
special problems that adolescents face and a description of how
the UNFPA designs and implements programs that address those
problems.
</P>
<P>
World Population Day was first celebrated in 1987, when the
world population reached 5 billion. The United Nations authorized
the event as a vehicle to build awareness of population issues and
the impact they have on development and the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
