<HEADLINE> Parties to Convention on Women Number 160 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Five more countries have
ratified the Convention on Elimination of All Forms of
Discrimination against Women in the past months this year,
bringing the total number of parties to the convention to 160, a
UN committee reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 17th session of the Committee on the Elimination
of Discrimination against Women on behalf of the secretary-general
and his special adviser on gender issues, Kristen Timonthy said
the convention had been ratified by the Kyrgyz Republic, Lebanon,
Mozambique, Switzerland and Turkmenistan since the 16th session of
the committee held last January.
</P>
<P>
The current session of the committee was a historic occasion as
it was the first time that it was meeting for a second annual
session, said Timothy, who was also deputy director of the
division for advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
She also informed the 23-member expert committee that
significant progress had been made towards the elaboration of an
optional complaints protocol to the convention.
</P>
<P>
The 17th session of the committee would last until July 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
