<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell to a nearly
four-week low against the yen today after Japan reported a surge
in its June trade surplus, refreshing concern that the U.S.
currency's strength is hurting American exporters.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar recovered from an early selloff against the mark
and ended higher against the pound, helped by British economic
data that showed unexpected manufacturing weakness.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the foreign-exchange volume was thin due to summer
vacations, exaggerating currency movements. But the rise in
Japan's surplus surprised the market.
</P>
<P>
The data showed Japan's surplus rose to 453.20 billion yen in
the first 20 days of June, far more than expected and more than
double the 197.65 billion yen surplus a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The dollar traded as low as 112.16 yen in intraday dealings
before settling in New York at 112.77 yen, down from 113.890 yen
Thursday and the lowest closing level since June 11.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also fell to an intraday low of 1.7421 marks before
recovering to settle at 1.7521 marks in New York, down from 1.7535
marks Thursday. The pound cost 1.6886 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6906 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday: 1.4610
Swiss francs, down from 1.4697; 5.9056 French francs, up from
5.9055; 1,706.00 Italian lire, up from 1,705.00; 1.3767 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3730. 
</P>
</TEXT>
