<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Reforms in Kenya's Power Sub-Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today announced
the approval of a 125 million U.S. dollar credit for Kenya to back
the government's reform in the power sub-sector.
</P>
<P>
The energy sector investment project, the total cost of which
is estimated at some 1 billion dollars, is designed to result in
the development of an efficient and viable energy sector to
support the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The project includes sector restructuring and reorganization,
legal and regulatory reforms for the power sub-sector and
facilitate private sector entry, power expansion and
rehabilitation at least-cost, including two 75 MW power plants in
Mombassa, two 32 MW power plants at Olkaria and a 60 MW hydropower
plant on the Sondu River.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be channeled through the International
Development Association (IDA), the concessionary lending arm of
the World Bank. In addition to the IDA credit, the Commonwealth
Development Corporation and the European Investment Bank are also
considering cofinancing the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
