<DOCNO> XIE19970708.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Predicts 3 Nations for NATO's Eastward Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
predicted today that only three nations would be invited to join
NATO at the alliance's Madrid summit which starts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton flew to the Spanish capital on the eve of the two-day
summit which faces a hard debate over whether to limit the
alliance's eastward expansion to three -- Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic -- or to include Slovenia and Romania as well.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the consensus decision will be for three, but I
hope and believe there will be a clear message that the door to
NATO remains open," Clinton told reporters after meeting with a
bi-partisan delegation of Republican and Democratic members of the
U.S. Congress in Spain for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Clinton clearly sought to soften his opposition to allowing
Romania and Slovenia NATO membership now, saying he was "very
enthusiastic about the developments that have taken place" in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
"I'm glad they want to be in NATO," he said, "and I think that
they should get consideration. I just don't think at this time
that they should be admitted."
</P>
<P>
France and Italy, supported by seven other NATO members
predominately from southern Europe, have lobbied hard for the
candidatures of Romania and Slovenia as well, in an effort to
avoid too heavy a shift in NATO's future orientation toward
Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
While reaffirming that five countries now fulfilled the
conditions for joining, France indicated in a statement on July 2
that it would not block the admission of only three countries if
Clinton insisted.
</P>
<P>
"The consensus has yet to be reached and the final decision
will be taken by the heads of state and government of the (NATO)
member states on Tuesday," a Senior NATO official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the 16 NATO leaders Tuesday would not
only make a decision regarding the expansion list, but also
announce "the policy of open door."
</P>
<P>
"NATO enlargement is not a one-shot operation... the leaders
will also give substances to NATO's declaration of open door," he
said.
</P>
<P>
It seems already clear that President Clinton will get his way
to limit the accession group to three.
</P>
<P>
"Now people are waiting to see what kind of language would be
used in the Communique due to be released on Tuesday regarding
NATO's commitment to include Romania and Slovenia in the second
wave, which will probably be announced in 1999 when the first
three formally join the alliance," an expert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
