<HEADLINE> Illegal Exports of British Beef Seized in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A shipment of 170 tons of illegally
exported British beef has been confiscated by German authorities
on the Baltic Sea island of Ruegen, reports reaching here today
said.
</P>
<P>
The beef, which was on its way to Russia, had been exported by
a Belgian firm using forged papers, a German official said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission confirmed last Friday that Belgian
authorities were investigating two Belgian firms involved in
exports of British beef in defiance of a worldwide ban.
</P>
<P>
It also said that about 1,600 tons of British beef had been
exported illegally using forged Belgian papers.
</P>
<P>
The ban on British beef exports was imposed in March 1996 after
scientists said that the so-called "mad cow" disease, officially
known as bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), could spread to
humans in the form of the deadly Creutzfeldt Jakob Disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
