<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslims, Croats Fail to Reach Joint Police Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Muslims and Croats today
failed again to sign an agreement on the establishment of a joint
police force in the Herzegovina-Neretva canton, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is the precondition demanded by the Muslim side
for a summit between Chairman of the Bosnian Presidency Alija
Izetbegovic and Croatian President Franjo Tudjman. The summit,
originally scheduled for June 30, has been postponed for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Fatima Leho, governor of the Herzegovina-Neretva canton, was
quoted as saying today that the agreement was not reached because
Croat representatives insist on establishing the ethnic balance of
the joint police force based on the current population structure.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim side wants to form the police force on the basis of
the pre-war 1991 census. The Herzegovina-Heretva canton covers
Mostar, which is largely Croat-dominated, with majorities of
Muslims and other nationalities fleeing as refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
